{"title_page": "2004 Indonesian presidential election", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2012}}\n{{Infobox election\n| election_name      = 2004 Indonesian presidential election\n| country            = Indonesia\n| type               = presidential\n| ongoing            = no\n| previous_election  = 1999 Indonesian presidential election\n| previous_year      = 1999\n| next_election      = 2009 Indonesian presidential election\n| next_year          = 2009\n| election_date      = 5 July 2004 (first round)<br />20 September 2004 (second round)\n| image1             = [[File:SusiloBambangYudhoyono.jpg|150x150px]]\n| nominee1           = [[Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono]]\n| party1             = Democratic Party (Indonesia)\n| running_mate1      = [[Jusuf Kalla]]\n| popular_vote1      = 69,266,350\n| percentage1        = 60.62%\n| image2             = [[File:President Megawati Sukarnoputri - Indonesia (cropped).jpg|150x150px]]\n| nominee2           = [[Megawati Sukarnoputri]]\n| party2             = Indonesian Democratic Party of Struggle\n| running_mate2      = [[Hasyim Muzadi]]\n| popular_vote2      = 44,990,704\n| percentage2        = 39.38%\n| map_image          = Map of 2004 Indonesian Presidential Election (2nd Round) - Provinces.svg\n| map_caption        = Results of the second round: the candidate with the majority of votes in each of the 32 [[provinces of Indonesia]]. Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono: <span style=\"color:#191970;\">blue</span>; Megawati Sukarnoputri: <span style=\"color:#8b0000;\">red</span>.\n| title              = President\n| before_election    = [[Megawati Sukarnoputri]]\n| before_party       = [[Indonesian Democratic Party of Struggle|PDI-P]]\n| after_election     = [[Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono]]\n| after_party        = Democratic Party (Indonesia)\n| 2blank = Logo\n| 2data1 = [[File:Logo Pemilu 2004.svg|100px]]\n| 3blank = Mascot\n| 3data1 = [[File:Maskot Pemilu 2004.svg|100px]]\n| 4blank = Mascot name\n| 4data1 = -}}{{Politics of Indonesia}}\n\nThe first [[Direct election|direct]] '''presidential election''' in Indonesia was held in [[Two-round system|two rounds]] on 5 July and 20 September 2004. Before a 2002 amendment to the [[Constitution of Indonesia]], the [[President of Indonesia|President]] and [[Vice President of Indonesia|Vice President]] were elected by the country's top legislative body, the [[People's Consultative Assembly]] (MPR).\n\nUnder the new amendment, a candidate pair is elected into office after receiving more than 50% of the vote nationally with at least 2% of the vote in more than half of the [[provinces of Indonesia]]. If no pair receives the number of votes required, the election will continue into the second round with the pairs receiving the highest and second-highest number of votes. Further regulations set by the General Election Commission (KPU) state that each pair must be nominated by a political party or coalition of parties which received at least 5% of the popular vote or 3% of the seats to the [[People's Representative Council]] (DPR) in the [[2004 Indonesian legislative election|April legislative election]].\n\nThe incumbent president, [[Megawati Sukarnoputri]], was sworn into office in 2001 after the legislature impeached and removed her predecessor, president [[Abdurrahman Wahid]] (often known as \"Gus Dur\"), from office. Megawati's re-election bid was challenged by four candidates, including incumbent vice president [[Hamzah Haz]]. In the first round, former [[Mutual Assistance Cabinet|cabinet]] member and retired general [[Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono]] received a [[Plurality (voting)|plurality]] of the valid ballots submitted, followed by Megawati. Yudhoyono eventually defeated Megawati with 60.62% of the valid ballots in the second round. He was inaugurated as the sixth president of Indonesia on 20 October 2004.\n\n==Background==\nIn the [[1999 Indonesian legislative election|1999 legislative election]], the [[Indonesian Democratic Party of Struggle]] (PDI-P) won the most number of seats in the DPR and became the largest faction in the MPR, the legislative body responsible for electing the [[President of Indonesia|President]]. The PDI\u2013P was led by [[Megawati Sukarnoputri]], daughter of [[Sukarno]], Indonesia's first president. Megawati's supporters had expected her to be elected president by the MPR, but she failed to reach out to parties other than the [[National Awakening Party]] (PKB). Her only opponent at the time was President [[B. J. Habibie]], who came into office in May 1998, but he withdrew his candidacy after his accountability speech was rejected by the MPR. The PKB, which was led by [[Abdurrahman Wahid]], the leader of Indonesia's largest Islamic organisation [[Nahdlatul Ulama]] (NU), had also pledged to support Megawati for President. However, it became clear that Megawati did not have enough votes to back her candidacy. Additionally, [[National Mandate Party]] (PAN) leader [[Amien Rais]] and his Central Axis ([[Indonesian language|Indonesian]]: ''Poros Tengah''), a coalition of Islamic and reform parties, began pushing for Abdurrahman's candidacy.<ref>{{Cite journal | last = Thompson | first = Eric C. | title = Indonesia in Transition: the 1999 Presidential Elections | url = http://www.nbr.org/publications/briefing/pdf/brief9.pdf | format = PDF | publisher = National Bureau of Asian Research | date = December 1999 | accessdate = 20 June 2009 | postscript = . | ref = harv | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20120925021128/http://www.nbr.org/publications/briefing/pdf/brief9.pdf | archive-date = 25 September 2012 | url-status = dead | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nAbdurrahman eventually won the MPR's presidential election, and Megawati was elected as [[Vice President of Indonesia|Vice President]].<ref name=\"AAS 11\">{{Harvnb|Ananta|Arifin|Suryadinata|2005|p=11|Ref=none}}</ref> As President, he repealed many of the laws enacted during the [[New Order (Indonesia)|Suharto era]] that discriminated against [[Chinese Indonesian]]s. Among these was the banning on the use of [[Chinese character]]s and display of images relating to Chinese culture. Following this act, many political parties began to reach out to Chinese Indonesians for their votes by displaying Chinese characters on campaign material.<ref>{{Cite news | last = Setiono | first = Benny G. | title = Etnis Tionghoa dan Partai Politik | url = http://www.indonesiamedia.com/2003/02/berta-0203-tionghoaparpol.htm | work = Indonesia Media | date = February 2003 | language = Indonesian | accessdate = 20 June 2009 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20081212061754/http://www.indonesiamedia.com/2003/02/berta-0203-tionghoaparpol.htm | archivedate = 12 December 2008 | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nFollowing Abdurrahman's impeachment and removal from office by the MPR in July 2001, the legislative body elevated Megawati to the presidency. She would complete the remainder of Abdurrahman's five-year term, ending in October 2004.<ref name=\"AAS 11\"/> During its 2002 annual session, the MPR added a series of amendments to the [[Constitution of Indonesia]],<ref>{{Cite news | last = Langit | first = Richel | title = Indonesia's military: Business as usual | url = http://www.atimes.com/atimes/Southeast_Asia/DH16Ae06.html | work = [[Asia Times Online]] | date = 16 August 2002 | accessdate =20 June 2009}}</ref> including the removal of the [[Indonesian military|military's]] 38 appointed seats in the Assembly, and an amendment for direct election of the President and Vice President. This presidential election process would involve political parties nominating a presidential and vice-presidential ticket with the option of a runoff election.<ref>{{Cite news | last = Aglionby | first = John | title = Indonesia takes a giant step down the road to democracy | url = https://www.theguardian.com/world/2002/aug/11/indonesia.johnaglionby | work = [[The Observer]] | date = 11 August 2002 | accessdate =10 June 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Candidates==\n[[File:Indonesia presidential polls 2004.png|thumb|400px|A series of tracking surveys conducted by the [[International Foundation for Electoral Systems]] between December 2003 and late June 2004 showed the popularity of each presidential candidate among voters throughout the selection and campaign periods.<ref>{{Cite journal | title = Results from Wave XIV of Tracking Surveys | url = http://www.ifes.org/publication/45d5b9ab8e448881607d9cf731703fe8/2004_Tracking_Survey_Results_from_WaveXIV.pdf | publisher = [[International Foundation for Electoral Systems]] | format = PDF | page = 5 | date = 1 July 2004 | accessdate = 28 June 2009 | postscript = . | ref = harv | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20081129001443/http://www.ifes.org/publication/45d5b9ab8e448881607d9cf731703fe8/2004_Tracking_Survey_Results_from_WaveXIV.pdf | archive-date = 29 November 2008 | url-status = dead | df = dmy-all }}</ref>]]\nIn December 2003, the [[International Foundation for Electoral Systems]] (IFES) began a tracking survey in order to assess the popularity of potential candidates. The survey continued until the start of the first election round on 5 July and included thirteen possible candidates for president. The first IFES survey indicated that incumbent President [[Megawati Sukarnoputri]] received a plurality of the votes. However, by the time of the [[2004 Indonesian legislative election|April 2004 legislative election]], retired General [[Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono]] had taken the lead from Megawati after resigning from her cabinet in March. Other potential candidates included DPR Speaker [[Akbar Tanjung]] and [[Yogyakarta Sultanate|Yogyakarta Sultan]] [[Hamengkubuwana X]].<ref name=\"AAS 67-69\">{{Harvnb|Ananta|Arifin|Suryadinata|2005|pp=67\u201369|Ref=none}}</ref>\n\nThe results of the legislative election determined which political parties were eligible to submit presidential tickets. Only parties which received at least 5% of the popular vote or 3% of seats (17 of 550 seats) in the DPR would be allowed to submit candidates. Parties that did not meet these criteria must join with other parties to meet at least one criterion.  Seven political parties met these criteria: the [[Golkar|Party of the Functional Groups]] (Golkar), the [[Indonesian Democratic Party of Struggle]] (PDI-P), the [[National Awakening Party]] (PKB), the [[United Development Party]] (PPP), the [[Democratic Party (Indonesia)|Democratic Party]] (PD), the [[Prosperous Justice Party]] (PKS), and the [[National Mandate Party]] (PAN). The PKS was the only party not to nominate candidates, but it later threw its support behind the PAN.<ref name=\"AAS 70\">{{Harvnb|Ananta|Arifin|Suryadinata|2005|p=70|Ref=none}}</ref>\n\nThe KPU announced the final list of candidates on 14 May. Following the announcement, all candidates were required to undergo medical screening. On 22 May, the Commission announced that the PKB's presidential candidate, former President [[Abdurrahman Wahid]], had failed the eye test and was not allowed to enter in the election.<ref name=\"AAS 70\"/> He initially told supporters not to vote for a presidential candidate on election day but decided to retract that statement after pressure from the party.<ref>{{Cite news | title = Gus Dur Tuntut KPU Rp 1 Triliun | url = http://www.suaramerdeka.com/harian/0405/23/nas01.htm | work = [[Suara Merdeka]] | date = 23 May 2004 | language = Indonesian | accessdate = 21 June 2009 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110716162053/http://www.suaramerdeka.com/harian/0405/23/nas01.htm | archive-date = 16 July 2011 | url-status = dead | df = dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news | title = Gus Dur Batal Ajak Golput | url = http://www.suaramerdeka.com/harian/0405/24/pem01.htm | work = [[Suara Merdeka]] | date = 24 May 2004 | language = Indonesian | accessdate = 21 June 2009 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20070630101141/http://www.suaramerdeka.com/harian/0405/24/pem01.htm | archive-date = 30 June 2007 | url-status = dead | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Wiranto and Salahuddin Wahid===\n{{Main|Wiranto|Salahuddin Wahid}}\nGolkar had won the April legislative election after losing to the PDI\u2013P five years prior. The party nominated retired General Wiranto and Salahuddin Wahid, deputy chairman of the National Human Rights Commission, for its presidential ticket. The pair was assigned the number '''1''' for its ballot.<ref name=\"Ballot\">{{Cite news | title = 5 Pasang Capres-Cawapres Peroleh Nomor Urut | url = http://www2.kompas.com/kompas-cetak/0405/24/utama/1040214.htm | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20040618082422/http://www.kompas.com/kompas-cetak/0405/24/utama/1040214.htm | work = [[Kompas]] | date = 24 May 2004 | language = Indonesian | archivedate = 18 June 2004 | accessdate =10 September 2009}}</ref>\n\nWiranto was an [[adjutant]] to former President [[Suharto]] in 1989\u20131993. During this time, he rapidly rose to the rank of full general and eventually became the head of the [[Indonesian National Armed Forces|National Armed Forces]].<ref name=\"AAS 71\">{{Harvnb|Ananta|Arifin|Suryadinata|2005|p=71|Ref=none}}</ref> When riots broke out throughout the country in 1998 against Suharto, he refused to take control in order to avoid the deaths of protesting university students. In 1999, as [[East Timor]] held an independence referendum, Wiranto was accused of having taken part in inciting violence among East Timorese along with several other officers; however, he was never issued an arrest warrant by [[Interpol]].<ref name=\"CNN Wiranto\">{{Cite news | last = Chew | first = Amy | title = Wiranto emerges as 2004 contender | url = http://edition.cnn.com/2003/WORLD/asiapcf/southeast/12/19/indonesia.wiranto/ | publisher = [[CNN]] | date = 22 December 2003 | accessdate =21 June 2009}}</ref> Under President Abdurrahman Wahid, Wiranto served as the Coordinating Minister for Political and Security Affairs but was later dismissed. On 20 April 2004, the Golkar Convention voted to nominate him for president over DPR Speaker Akbar Tanjung in the second round of voting.<ref name=\"AAS 71\"/>\n\nOn 9 May, Golkar selected Salahuddin Wahid (also known as Gus Sholah) as its vice-presidential candidate after an endorsement was made by his brother Abdurrahman.<ref>{{Cite news | title = Golkar picks Gus Solah as VP candidate | url = http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2004/05/10/golkar-picks-gus-solah-vp-candidate.html | work = [[The Jakarta Post]] | date = 10 May 2004 | accessdate = 28 June 2009 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110607121810/http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2004/05/10/golkar-picks-gus-solah-vp-candidate.html | archivedate = 7 June 2011 | df = dmy-all }}</ref> Because Salahuddin was also a deputy chairman of the Central Board of [[Nahdlatul Ulama]], many NU members criticised him for not adhering to the organisation's ''khittah'', which affirmed the NU's status as a non-political organisation.<ref name=\"Khittah\">{{Cite book | last = Fealy | first = Greg | editor1-last = Reid | editor1-first = Anthony | editor1-link = Anthony Reid (academic) | editor2-last = Gilsenan | editor2-first = Michael | lastauthoramp = yes | title = Islamic Legitimacy in a Plural Asia | chapter = The political contingency of reform-mindedness in Indonesia's Nahdlatul Ulama: interest politics and the ''Khittah'' | publisher = Routledge | place = London | year = 2007 | page = 163 | isbn = 0-415-45173-6}}</ref> With this nomination, PKB leaders officially supported the Wiranto\u2013Salahuddin pair for the election.<ref name=\"AAS 71\"/>\n\nSalahuddin's position on the human rights commission helped the reputation of Wiranto. However, because both candidates were of [[Javanese people|Javanese]] background, they were not expected to attract as many voters who were not Javanese.<ref name=\"AAS 71\"/>\n\n===Megawati Sukarnoputri and Hasyim Muzadi===\n{{Main|Megawati Sukarnoputri|Hasyim Muzadi}}\nIncumbent President Megawati Sukarnoputri was the PDI\u2013P's top nominee. She was joined by vice-presidential candidate Hasyim Muzadi, general chairman of Indonesia's largest Islamic organisation Nahdlatul Ulama (NU). The pair was assigned the number '''2''' for its ballot.<ref name=\"Ballot\"/>\n\nAccording to a report released by the [[National Democratic Institute for International Affairs]], Megawati has a \"unique burden of being the only candidate in the race who is held responsible for the current situation most voters are unhappy with\" although several other candidates have been members of her government.<ref name=\"NDI\">{{Cite journal | title = The People's Voice: Presidential Politics and Voter Perspectives in Indonesia | url = http://www.ndi.org/files/1729_id_focusgroups.pdf | format = PDF | date = June 2004 | publisher = [[National Democratic Institute for International Affairs]] | accessdate = 28 June 2009 | postscript = . | ref = harv | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20081129125402/http://www.ndi.org/files/1729_id_focusgroups.pdf | archivedate = 29 November 2008 | df = dmy-all }}</ref> However, the general discontent for her presidency was attributed mainly to the failure of the government to communicate Megawati's achievements rather than the state of the country itself.<ref name=\"AAS 91\">{{Harvnb|Ananta|Arifin|Suryadinata|p=91|Ref=none}}</ref> The PDI\u2013P came in second during the April legislative election with 18.5% of the votes, a reduction by almost half from the 33.7% it had received in 1999.<ref name=\"AAS 22\">{{Harvnb|Ananta|Arifin|Suryadinata|2005|p=22|Ref=none}}</ref>\n\nHasyim Muzadi had been mentioned as a possible running mate for Megawati as early as November 2003.<ref>{{Cite news | last = Pereira | first = Derwin | title = Who will be Mega's running mate? | work = [[The Straits Times]] | date = 7 November 2003}}</ref> His candidacy was officially announced by Megawati on 6 May.<ref>{{Cite news | title = Megawati Memilih Hasyim Muzadi Sebagai Calon Wakil Presiden | url = http://www.voanews.com/indonesian/archive/2004-05/a-2004-05-06-10-1.cfm | publisher = [[Voice of America]] | date = 6 May 2004 | language = Indonesian | accessdate =28 June 2009}}</ref> As Chairman of the Central Board of Nahdlatul Ulama, he was criticised by many NU members for not adhering to the organisation's ''khittah'' and the principle of political neutrality.<ref name=\"Khittah\"/> Muslim intellectual [[Nurcholish Madjid]] had called on him to step down from the position following the announcement of the candidacy.<ref>{{Cite news | last = Arvian | first = Yandhrie | title = Cak Nur: Hasyim Muzadi Khianati Khitah NU | url = http://www.tempointeraktif.com/hg/nasional/2004/05/06/brk,20040506-23,id.html | work = [[Tempo magazine (Indonesia)|Tempo]] | date = 6 May 2004 | language = Indonesian | accessdate = 28 June 2009 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20080908052913/http://www.tempointeraktif.com/hg/nasional/2004/05/06/brk,20040506-23,id.html | archive-date = 8 September 2008 | url-status = dead | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe two candidates' Javanese background were not expected to attract as many non-Javanese voters.<ref name=\"AAS 71\"/> However, the candidates' status as civilians attracted those who did not favour candidates with a military background, and they also were expected to attract both secular and religious voters.<ref name=\"AAS 72\">{{Harvnb|Ananta|Arifin|Suryadinata|2005|p=72|Ref=none}}</ref>\n\n===Amien Rais and Siswono Yudohusodo===\n{{Main|Amien Rais|Siswono Yudohusodo}}\nThe PAN nominated Amien Rais, chairman of the MPR, as its presidential candidate. His running mate was Siswono Yudohusodo. The pair was assigned the number '''3''' for its ballot.<ref name=\"Ballot\"/>\n\nAmien Rais had once served as the chairman of [[Muhammadiyah]]. However, despite leading the second-largest Islamic organisation in Indonesia, Amien established the PAN following the resignation of President Suharto as a party not based on religious affiliation. He became an influential figure in the early days of the reform period and was eventually elected to lead the MPR.<ref name=\"AAS 12\">{{Harvnb|Ananta|Arifin|Suryadinata|2005|p=12|Ref=none}}</ref> Among voters, he was seen as a candidate who had no association with the [[Political corruption|corruption]] that was endemic to the nation's government. Voters also saw him as an ambitious person and as one who was known for being an [[orator]].<ref name=\"NDI\"/> Amien's party had received 6.4% of the votes during the legislative election.<ref name=\"AAS 22\"/>\n\nOn the other hand, Siswono Yudohusodo was a relative newcomer to the political scene. He served as the chairman of the Indonesian Farmers' Association (HKTI) and held ministerial positions during the later years of Suharto's presidency.<ref name=\"AAS 72\"/> Siswono was the wealthiest of any candidate for president or vice president based on reports submitted by candidates to the [[Corruption Eradication Commission]].<ref>{{Cite news | last = Sri Saraswati | first = Muninggar | title = Siswono the richest, Amien poorest candidate | url = http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2004/07/03/siswono-richest-amien-poorest-candidate.html | work = [[The Jakarta Post]] | date = 3 July 2004 | accessdate = 29 June 2009 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110607121831/http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2004/07/03/siswono-richest-amien-poorest-candidate.html | archivedate = 7 June 2011 | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nLike Megawati and Hasyim, Amien and Siswono were also not expected to attract many non-Javanese voters. The pair was supported by the PKS, the seventh party which met the criteria to submit presidential and vice-presidential candidates but did not do so, and a number of smaller parties.<ref name=\"AAS 72\"/>\n\n===Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono and Jusuf Kalla===\n{{Main|Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono|Jusuf Kalla}}\n[[File:Yudhoyono campaign rally 2004.jpg|thumb|The rapid rise in Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono's (center) popularity helped the Democratic Party garner 7.45% of votes during the April 2004 legislative election.<ref name=\"AAS 56\">{{Harvnb|Ananta|Arifin|Suryadinata|2005|p=56|Ref=none}}</ref>]]\nThe Democratic Party, supported by the [[Indonesian Justice and Unity Party]] (PKPI) and [[Crescent Star Party (Indonesia)|Crescent Star Party]] (PBB), nominated retired General Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono for its presidential candidate. He was later joined by Jusuf Kalla as running mate, and the pair was assigned the number '''4''' for its ballot.<ref name=\"Ballot\"/>\n\nSusilo Bambang Yudhoyono has served in the cabinets of two previous administrations. While serving as Coordinating Minister for Political, Social and Security Affairs under Abdurrahman Wahid, he refused an order to declare a [[state of emergency]] that would have stopped the parliamentary process to impeach the President and was subsequently dismissed.<ref>{{Harvnb|Ricklefs|2008|p=395|Ref=none}}</ref> Yudhoyono was nominated for vice president after the MPR selected Megawati to succeed Abdurrahman Wahid, but he lost the election to PPP Chairman Hamzah Haz and DPR Speaker Akbar Tanjung.<ref name=\"AAS 23\">{{Harvnb|Ananta|Arifin|Suryadinata|2005|p=23|Ref=none}}</ref> He reprised his prior cabinet position in Megawati's administration but resigned on 1 March 2004 to join the race for the presidency.<ref name=\"AAS 72\"/> The Democratic Party, established as a vehicle for Yudhoyono's political career by secular nationalists who saw the potential of his leadership,<ref name=\"AAS 23\"/> received 7.45% of votes and 10% of DPR seats in the April legislative election.<ref name=\"AAS 22\"/>\n\nYudhoyono's running mate was Jusuf Kalla, a wealthy [[Bugis]] businessman and member of Golkar who served as Coordinating Minister for People's Welfare under Megawati.<ref name=\"AAS 73\">{{Harvnb|Ananta|Arifin|Suryadinata|2005|p=73|Ref=none}}</ref> He mediated two separate peaceful resolutions to inter-religious conflicts between Christians and Muslims in his native [[Sulawesi]] in 2001 and [[Maluku Islands|Maluku]] in 2002.<ref>{{Cite news | last1 = Muannas | last2 = Amir | first2 = Syarief | title = Deklarasi Malino Mengakhiri Pertikaian di Poso | url = http://www.tempointeraktif.com/hg/nasional/2001/12/20/brk,20011220-26,id.html | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20041130232806/http://www.tempointeraktif.com/hg/nasional/2001/12/20/brk,20011220-26,id.html | url-status = dead | archive-date = 30 November 2004 | work = [[Tempo magazine (Indonesia)|Tempo]] | date = 20 December 2001 | language = Indonesian | accessdate = 10 September 2009 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite book | last = Hadi | first = Syamsul | title = Disintegrasi Pasca Orde Baru: Negara, Konflik Lokal dan Dinamika Internasional | language = Indonesian | page = 179 | publisher = Centre for International Relations Studies | place = Jakarta | year = 2007 | isbn = 979-461-624-9}}</ref> Kalla joined Golkar's selection process for the party's presidential nominee in August 2003 but withdrew his candidacy days before the party convention the following April.<ref>{{Cite news | title = Wiranto dan Kalla Maju, Agum Gumelar Mundur | url = http://www.kompas.com/kompas-cetak/0308/07/nasional/480103.htm | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20030808015457/http://www.kompas.com/kompas-cetak/0308/07/nasional/480103.htm | work = [[Kompas]] | date = 7 August 2003 | language = Indonesian | archivedate = 8 August 2003 | accessdate =10 September 2009}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news | title = Kalla Mundur Sebelum Konvensi | url = http://www.radarsulteng.com/berita/index.asp?Berita=Utama&id=30947 | work = Radar Sulteng | date = 16 April 2004 | language = Indonesian | accessdate = 10 September 2009 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20111008214105/http://www.radarsulteng.com/berita/index.asp?Berita=Utama&id=30947 | archive-date = 8 October 2011 | url-status = dead | df = dmy-all }}</ref> Several days later, he resigned his cabinet position and announced his alliance with Yudhoyono.<ref name=\"AAS 73\"/> Kalla was also seen as a potential vice-presidential candidate for the incumbent Megawati.<ref>{{Cite news | title = Blow to Megawati re-election bid | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/asia-pacific/3638903.stm | publisher = [[BBC]] | date = 19 April 2004 | accessdate =10 September 2009}}</ref>\n\nThe combination brought together two men with very different backgrounds that added to the attractiveness of their ticket. Yudhoyono, who was raised in densely populated Java, is seen as more secular and has a military background. On the other hand, Kalla is a devout Muslim who grew up in the outer province of South Sulawesi and came from a civilian background.<ref name=\"AAS 73\"/>\n\n===Hamzah Haz and Agum Gumelar===\n{{Main|Hamzah Haz|Agum Gumelar}}\nIncumbent Vice President Hamzah Haz was the presidential nominee of the PPP. He was joined by Minister of Transportation Agum Gumelar for the vice-presidential candidate. The pair was assigned the number '''5''' for its ballot.<ref name=\"Ballot\"/>\n\nHamzah Haz was elected vice president by the MPR after defeating DPR Speaker Akbar Tanjung when it removed President Abdurrahman Wahid from office in 2001. Although the [[BBC]] reported him once stating that \"no woman was fit to head the world's leading Muslim nation\", he came into office as the deputy to Indonesia's first female president. Haz served in the cabinet of President [[B. J. Habibie]] and was the first minister to resign from the Abdurrahman Wahid administration. He was accused of [[Political corruption#Graft|graft]] and [[nepotism]] but was never subjected to an investigation.<ref>{{Cite news | title = Profile: Hamzah Haz | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/asia-pacific/1457865.stm | publisher = [[BBC]] | date = 26 July 2001 | accessdate =12 September 2009}}</ref> As Vice President, Haz had been a proponent of an amendment to the Constitution which would impose [[Sharia|Islamic law]] on Muslims in the country. However, other political parties and the Islamic organisations Nahdlatul Ulama and Muhammadiyah opposed such amendment for fear of more extreme forms of Islam.<ref>{{Harvnb|Ricklefs|2008|p=400|Ref=none}}</ref>\n\nA relatively unknown figure in the political scene, Agum Gumelar served as Minister of Transportation under Abdurrahman Wahid and Megawati.<ref name=\"AAS 73\"/> In September 2003, Agum had recommended Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono or Jusuf Kalla as Megawati's running mate in the presidential election after predicting that the PDI\u2013P would lose a significant number of votes in the April legislative election. However, both men eventually formed their own ticket, and Agum declined a vice-presidential candidate offer from Amien Rais in order to remain on the cabinet. He eventually accepted an offer from the PPP leadership to become Haz's running mate and resigned from Megawati's administration.<ref>{{Cite web | last1 = Cahyana | first1 = Ludhi | last2 = Parlan | first2 = Tri Mariyani | title = Hamzah Haz dan Agum Gumelar | url = http://www.isai.or.id/?q=node/20 | publisher = Institute for the Studies on Free Flow of Information | language = Indonesian | accessdate = 12 September 2009 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110721063726/http://www.isai.or.id/?q=node%2F20 | archivedate = 21 July 2011 | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nNeither candidate was of Javanese origin; hence, they might have attracted constituencies of the outer provinces.<ref name=\"AAS 73\"/>\n\n==Campaign==\n[[Political corruption|Corruption]], [[collusion]], and [[nepotism]] are the most consistently cited concerns among voters surveyed by the [[National Democratic Institute for International Affairs]].<ref name=\"NDI\"/>\n\n===Schedule===\n* 1 June 2004: All candidates sign the commitment of readiness to accept victory or defeat and to conduct a fair campaign.<ref name=\"Menang Kalah\">{{Cite news | title = Semua Calon Siap Menang dan Kalah | url = http://www2.kompas.com/kompas-cetak/0406/02/utama/1059733.htm | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20040622130535/http://www.kompas.com/kompas-cetak/0406/02/utama/1059733.htm | work = [[Kompas]] | date = 2 June 2004 | language = Indonesian | archivedate = 22 June 2004 | accessdate =10 September 2009}}</ref> Campaign period begins.<ref>{{Cite news | title = Jadwal Kampanye Pemilu Presiden | url = http://www.tempointeraktif.com/hg/narasi/2004/05/27/nrs,20040527-01,id.html | work = [[Tempo magazine (Indonesia)|Tempo]] | date = 27 May 2004 | language = Indonesian | accessdate = 21 June 2009 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20090623212306/http://www.tempointeraktif.com/hg/narasi/2004/05/27/nrs,20040527-01,id.html | archive-date = 23 June 2009 | url-status = dead | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n* 1 July 2004: Campaign period ends.\n* 5 July 2004: '''First round of voting'''.\n* 20 September 2004: '''Second round of voting'''.\n* 4 October 2004: Official second round results announced.<ref>{{Cite news | last = Purwanto | title = Presiden Terpilih Ditetapkan Sore Ini | url = http://www.tempointeraktif.com/hg/nasional/2004/10/04/brk,20041004-21,id.html | work = [[Tempo magazine (Indonesia)|Tempo]] | date = 4 October 2004 | language = Indonesian | accessdate = 21 June 2009 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20090614234242/http://www.tempointeraktif.com/hg/nasional/2004/10/04/brk,20041004-21,id.html | archive-date = 14 June 2009 | url-status = dead | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n* 20 October 2004: Inauguration of the President-elect and Vice President-elect.\n\n==Results==\nFormer security minister [[Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono]] won the first round with 33% of the vote. Incumbent President [[Megawati Sukarnoputri]] was second with 26%, ahead of former armed forces chief [[Wiranto]] on 22%. Yudhoyono did not do as well as earlier opinion polls had suggested, while Megawati did better. This was attributed by Indonesian observers to Yudhoyono's lack of a nationwide party machine, such as Megawati's PDI-P and Wiranto's Golkar.{{Citation needed|date=June 2009}}\n\nThe counting of 113 million votes, already a massive task in such a large and diverse country, was made more difficult by problems with the ballot papers.  Voters cast their ballots by making a hole in the ballot paper with a nail, above the photo of their preferred candidate. Because the ballot paper was handed to voters folded in half, many made the hole without unfolding the ballot, thus making two holes and invalidating their vote. Hundreds of thousands of these votes were invalidated before the General Election Committee (KPU) ruled that such ballots should be accepted.<ref>{{Cite news | last = Harsono | first = Andreas | title = Megawati Crawls In While Wiranto Cries Foul | url = http://www.irrawaddy.org/article.php?art_id=3657 | work = [[The Irrawaddy]] | date = 8 July 2004 | accessdate = 21 June 2009 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20100811195324/http://irrawaddy.org/article.php?art_id=3657 | archivedate = 11 August 2010 | df = dmy-all }}</ref> This necessitated recounts in many places, slowing the count and raising fears of a disputed result.\n{{electiontable|Indonesian presidential election, 2004|editlink=no}}\nSummary of the 5 July and 20 September 2004 [[Indonesia]]n presidential election results\n|-\n! style=\"background-color:#E9E9E9;text-align:left;\" rowspan=2 |Candidate\n! style=\"background-color:#E9E9E9;text-align:left;\" rowspan=2 |Running mate\n! style=\"background-color:#E9E9E9;text-align:left;\" rowspan=2 |Party\n! style=\"background-color:#E9E9E9;text-align:center;\" colspan=2 |First round\n! style=\"background-color:#E9E9E9;text-align:center;\" colspan=2 |Second round\n|-\n! style=\"background-color:#E9E9E9;text-align:center;\" |Votes\n! style=\"background-color:#E9E9E9;text-align:center;\" |%\n! style=\"background-color:#E9E9E9;text-align:center;\" |Votes\n! style=\"background-color:#E9E9E9;text-align:center;\" |%\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | '''[[Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono]]'''\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | '''[[Jusuf Kalla]]'''\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |'''[[Democratic Party (Indonesia)|Democratic Party]]''' (''Partai Demokrat'')\n|'''39,838,184'''\n|'''33.57'''\n|'''69,266,350'''\n|'''60.62'''\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | '''[[Megawati Sukarnoputri]]'''\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | '''[[Hasyim Muzadi]]'''\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |'''[[Indonesian Democratic Party \u2013 Struggle]]''' (''Partai Demokrasi Indonesia Perjuangan'')\n|'''31,569,104'''\n|'''26.61'''\n|44,990,704\n|39.38\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Wiranto]]\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Salahuddin Wahid]]\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Golongan Karya|Party of the Functional Groups]] (''Partai Golongan Karya'')\n|26,286,788\n|22.15\n|style=\"background-color:#E9E9E9\" colspan=2 rowspan=3| \n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Amien Rais]]\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Siswono Yudohusodo]]\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[National Mandate Party]] (''Partai Amanat Nasional'')\n|17,392,931\n|14.66\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Hamzah Haz]]\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Agum Gumelar]]\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[United Development Party]] (''Partai Persatuan Pembangunan'')\n|3,569,861\n|3.01\n|-\n|style=\"background-color:#E9E9E9\" colspan=7|\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" colspan=3 |'''Total'''\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" |'''118,656,868'''\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" |100.00\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" |'''114,257,054'''\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" |100.00\n|-\n| colspan=7 style=\"text-align:left;\" |Source: {{Harvnb|Ananta|Arifin|Suryadinata|2005|pp=80\u201383, 107}}\n|}\n\n===First round===\n[[File:Map of 2004 Indonesian Presidential Election (1st Round) - Provinces.svg|thumb|600px|center|Results of the first round: the candidate with the majority of votes in each of the 32 [[provinces of Indonesia]].<ref>Compiled from {{Harvnb|Ananta|Arifin|Suryadinata|2005|Ref=none}}, table 3.3</ref><br/>Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono: <span style=\"color:#191970;\">dark blue</span>; Megawati Sukarnoputri: <span style=\"color:#8b0000;\">red</span>; Wiranto: <span style=\"color:yellow;\">yellow</span>; Amien Rais: <span style=\"color:#9ec7f3;\">light blue</span>.]]\nWiranto refused to accept the election results and petitioned the [[Indonesian Constitutional Court|Constitutional Court]]. Wiranto and Salahuddin argued that, due to irregularities in ballot counting by the KPU, they had lost 5,434,660 votes from twenty-six provinces. Those ballots would have made the total popular vote for the pair higher than that for Megawati and Hasyim, putting the former pair instead of the latter in the second round. However, the Court ruled on 10 August that it found no irregularities and upheld the Commission's final count.<ref>{{Harvnb|Ananta|Arifin|Suryadinata|2005|p=69|Ref=none}}</ref>\n\n====Analysis====\n\n===Second round===\n[[File:Map of 2004 Indonesian Presidential Election (2nd Round) - Provinces.svg|thumb|600px|center|Results of the second round: the candidate with the majority of votes in each of the 32 [[provinces of Indonesia]].<ref>Compiled from {{Harvnb|Ananta|Arifin|Suryadinata|2005|Ref=none}}, table 4.3</ref><br/>Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono: <span style=\"color:#191970;\">dark blue</span>; Megawati Sukarnoputri: <span style=\"color:#8b0000;\">red</span>.]]\n\n====Analysis====\n\n==Reactions==\n*'''[[Indonesia]]:''' President [[Megawati Sukarnoputri]] said in a speech on Armed Forces Day, 5 October, \"We have to show to the world we are a big nation. All components of the nation have to stick to the agreement we have struck that whoever is elected in the democratic election has to be accepted. We may have chosen differently. However, we had the same objective: that is to bring the nation to a better future.\"<ref>{{Cite news | last = Moore | first = Matthew | title = Megawati still keeping Yudhoyono on hold | url = http://www.smh.com.au/articles/2004/10/05/1096949513009.html | work = [[The Sydney Morning Herald]] | publisher = [[Fairfax Media]] | date = 6 October 2004 | accessdate =20 June 2009}}</ref>\n*'''[[Australia]]''': Prime Minister [[John Howard]] planned to attend Yudhoyono's inauguration. Howard said, \"I look forward to working closely with Dr. Yudhoyono and his new government to continue and extend the close cooperation between our two nations, particularly on counter-terrorism.\"<ref>{{Cite news | last = Forbes | first = Mark | title = PM to see new leader sworn in | url = http://www.theage.com.au/articles/2004/10/14/1097607368339.html | newspaper = [[The Age]] | publisher = [[Fairfax Media]] | date = 15 October 2004 | accessdate =20 June 2009}}</ref>\n*'''[[People's Republic of China]]''': [[Politburo Standing Committee of the Communist Party of China|Politburo Standing Committee]] member [[Wu Guanzheng]] met with Yudhoyono on 13 October and conveyed congratulations from President [[Hu Jintao]].<ref>{{Cite news | title = Senior Chinese leader meets Indonesia's president-elect | url = http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2004-10/15/content_2091733.htm | agency = [[Xinhua News Agency]] | date = 14 October 2004 | accessdate =20 June 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Aftermath==\n{{Wikinews|Indonesia's president visits victims of tsunami}}\n[[Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono]] and [[Jusuf Kalla]] were sworn in as president and vice president on 20 October. It was the first Indonesian presidential inauguration to be attended by foreign leaders.<ref>{{Harvnb|Ananta|Arifin|Suryadinata|2005|p=121|Ref=none}}</ref> After a selection process that began on 15 October, the [[United Indonesia Cabinet]] was announced later following the inauguration. The 36-member cabinet was sworn in at the [[Istana Negara, Jakarta|State Palace]] on 21 October.<ref>{{Harvnb|Ananta|Arifin|Suryadinata|2005|p=128|Ref=none}}</ref> The process of selecting candidates for Yudhoyono's cabinet was considered \"decent, intelligent, and indecisive\". While attempting to satisfy as many members as possible in his coalition of small parties, Yudhoyono created a cabinet that was neither quite as cohesive nor effective. However, Kalla soon became the party chairman of Golkar in late 2004 and turned the party's votes in the DPR to those in favour of the government, creating an effective ''bloc'' and leaving Megawati's PDI\u2013P as the largest non-government party in the DPR.<ref>{{Harvnb|Ricklefs|2008|pp=404\u2013405|Ref=none}}</ref> Although the first one hundred days of Yudhoyono's administration saw continuing economic stability, it was overshadowed by the events of the [[2004 Indian Ocean earthquake|Indian Ocean earthquake]] which occurred on 26 December. The earthquake triggered [[tsunami]]s that destroyed the coastline of the provinces of [[Aceh]] and [[North Sumatra]] and killed more than 200,000 people.<ref>{{Harvnb|Ananta|Arifin|Suryadinata|2005|pp=132\u2013133|Ref=none}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Indonesia}}\n* [[Elections in Indonesia]]\n* [[2004 Indonesian legislative election]]\n* [[Two-round system]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==References==\n* {{Cite book | last1 = Ananta | first1 = Aris | last2 = Arifin | first2 = Evi Nurvidya | last3 = Suryadinata | first3 = Leo | lastauthoramp = yes | title = Emerging Democracy in Indonesia | place = Singapore | publisher = Institute of Southeast Asian Studies | year = 2005 | isbn = 978-981-230-322-6 | postscript = . | ref = harv}}\n* {{Cite book |first=Bob S. |last=Hadiwinata |title=The 2004 Parliamentary and Presidential Elections in Indonesia |work=Between Consolidation and Crisis: Elections and Democracy in Five Nations in Southeast Asia |publisher=Lit |place=Berlin |year=2006 |pages=85\u2013146}}\n* {{Cite book | last = Koirudin | title = Kilas Balik Pemilihan Presiden 2004 | place = Yogyakarta | publisher = Pustaka Pelajar | year = 2004 | language = Indonesian | isbn = 979-3721-11-1 | postscript = . | ref = harv}}\n* {{Cite book | last = Ricklefs | first = M. C. | authorlink = M. C. Ricklefs | title = A History of Modern Indonesia since c. 1200 | year = 2008 | publisher = Stanford University Press | place = Stanford, CA | edition = 4th | isbn = 0-8047-6130-2 | postscript = . | ref = harv}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.kpu.go.id General Election Commission]\n\n{{Indonesian elections}}\n\n[[Category:2004 elections in Asia]]\n[[Category:2004 in Indonesia|Presidential election]]\n[[Category:Presidential elections in Indonesia|2004]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2012}}\n{{Infobox election\n| election_name      = 2004 Indonesian presidential election\n| country            = Indonesia\n| type               = presidential\n| ongoing            = no\n| previous_election  = 1999 Indonesian presidential election\n| previous_year      = 1999\n| next_election      = 2009 Indonesian presidential election\n| next_year          = 2009\n| election_date      = 5 July 2004 (first round)<br />20 September 2004 (second round)\n| image1             = [[File:SusiloBambangYudhoyono.jpg|150x150px]]\n| nominee1           = [[Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono]]\n| party1             = Democratic Party (Indonesia)\n| running_mate1      = [[Jusuf Kalla]]\n| popular_vote1      = 69,266,350\n| percentage1        = 60.62%\n| image2             = [[File:President Megawati Sukarnoputri - Indonesia (cropped).jpg|150x150px]]\n| nominee2           = [[Megawati Sukarnoputri]]\n| party2             = Indonesian Democratic Party of Struggle\n| running_mate2      = [[Hasyim Muzadi]]\n| popular_vote2      = 44,990,704\n| percentage2        = 39.38%\n| map_image          = Map of 2004 Indonesian Presidential Election (2nd Round) - Provinces.svg\n| map_caption        = Results of the second round: the candidate with the majority of votes in each of the 32 [[provinces of Indonesia]]. Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono: <span style=\"color:#191970;\">blue</span>; Megawati Sukarnoputri: <span style=\"color:#8b0000;\">red</span>.\n| title              = President\n| before_election    = [[Megawati Sukarnoputri]]\n| before_party       = [[Indonesian Democratic Party of Struggle|PDI-P]]\n| after_election     = [[Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono]]\n| after_party        = Democratic Party (Indonesia)\n| 2blank = Logo\n| 2data1 = [[File:Logo Pemilu 2004.svg|100px]]\n| 3blank = Mascot\n| 3data1 = [[File:Maskot Pemilu 2004.svg|100px]]\n| 4blank = Mascot name\n| 4data1 = -}}{{Politics of Indonesia}}\n\nThe first [[Direct election|direct]] '''presidential election''' in Indonesia was held in [[Two-round system|two rounds]] on 5 July and 20 September 2004. Before a 2002 amendment to the [[Constitution of Indonesia]], the [[President of Indonesia|President]] and [[Vice President of Indonesia|Vice President]] were elected by the country's top legislative body, the [[People's Consultative Assembly]] (MPR).\n\nUnder the new amendment, a candidate pair is elected into office after receiving more than 50% of the vote nationally with at least 2% of the vote in more than half of the [[provinces of Indonesia]]. If no pair receives the number of votes required, the election will continue into the second round with the pairs receiving the highest and second-highest number of votes. Further regulations set by the General Election Commission (KPU) state that each pair must be nominated by a political party or coalition of parties which received at least 5% of the popular vote or 3% of the seats to the [[People's Representative Council]] (DPR) in the [[2004 Indonesian legislative election|April legislative election]].\n\nThe incumbent President, [[Megawati Sukarnoputri]], was sworn into office in 2001 after the legislature impeached and removed her predecessor, president [[Abdurrahman Wahid]] (often known as \"Gus Dur\"), from office. Megawati's re-election bid was challenged by four candidates, including incumbent Vice President [[Hamzah Haz]]. In the first round, former [[Mutual Assistance Cabinet|cabinet]] member and retired General [[Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono]] received a [[Plurality (voting)|plurality]] of the valid ballots submitted, followed by Megawati. Yudhoyono eventually defeated Megawati with 60.62% of the valid ballots in the second round. He was inaugurated as the sixth President of Indonesia on 20 October 2004.\n\n==Background==\nIn the [[1999 Indonesian legislative election|1999 legislative election]], the [[Indonesian Democratic Party of Struggle]] (PDI-P) won the most number of seats in the DPR and became the largest faction in the MPR, the legislative body responsible for electing the [[President of Indonesia|President]]. The PDI\u2013P was led by [[Megawati Sukarnoputri]], daughter of [[Sukarno]], Indonesia's first president. Megawati's supporters had expected her to be elected President by the MPR, but she failed to reach out to parties other than the [[National Awakening Party]] (PKB). Her only opponent at the time was President [[B. J. Habibie]], who came into office in May 1998, but he withdrew his candidacy after his accountability speech was rejected by the MPR. The PKB, which was led by [[Abdurrahman Wahid]], the leader of Indonesia's largest Islamic organisation [[Nahdlatul Ulama]] (NU), had also pledged to support Megawati for President. However, it became clear that Megawati did not have enough votes to back her candidacy. Additionally, [[National Mandate Party]] (PAN) leader [[Amien Rais]] and his Central Axis ([[Indonesian language|Indonesian]]: ''Poros Tengah''), a coalition of Islamic and reform parties, began pushing for Abdurrahman's candidacy.<ref>{{Cite journal | last = Thompson | first = Eric C. | title = Indonesia in Transition: the 1999 Presidential Elections | url = http://www.nbr.org/publications/briefing/pdf/brief9.pdf | format = PDF | publisher = National Bureau of Asian Research | date = December 1999 | accessdate = 20 June 2009 | postscript = . | ref = harv | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20120925021128/http://www.nbr.org/publications/briefing/pdf/brief9.pdf | archive-date = 25 September 2012 | url-status = dead | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nAbdurrahman eventually won the MPR's presidential election, and Megawati was elected as [[Vice President of Indonesia|Vice President]].<ref name=\"AAS 11\">{{Harvnb|Ananta|Arifin|Suryadinata|2005|p=11|Ref=none}}</ref> As President, he repealed many of the laws enacted during the [[New Order (Indonesia)|Suharto era]] that discriminated against [[Chinese Indonesian]]s. Among these was the banning on the use of [[Chinese character]]s and display of images relating to Chinese culture. Following this act, many political parties began to reach out to Chinese Indonesians for their votes by displaying Chinese characters on campaign material.<ref>{{Cite news | last = Setiono | first = Benny G. | title = Etnis Tionghoa dan Partai Politik | url = http://www.indonesiamedia.com/2003/02/berta-0203-tionghoaparpol.htm | work = Indonesia Media | date = February 2003 | language = Indonesian | accessdate = 20 June 2009 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20081212061754/http://www.indonesiamedia.com/2003/02/berta-0203-tionghoaparpol.htm | archivedate = 12 December 2008 | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nFollowing Abdurrahman's impeachment and removal from office by the MPR in July 2001, the legislative body elevated Megawati to the presidency. She would complete the remainder of Abdurrahman's five-year term, ending in October 2004.<ref name=\"AAS 11\"/> During its 2002 annual session, the MPR added a series of amendments to the [[Constitution of Indonesia]],<ref>{{Cite news | last = Langit | first = Richel | title = Indonesia's military: Business as usual | url = http://www.atimes.com/atimes/Southeast_Asia/DH16Ae06.html | work = [[Asia Times Online]] | date = 16 August 2002 | accessdate =20 June 2009}}</ref> including the removal of the [[Indonesian military|military's]] 38 appointed seats in the Assembly, and an amendment for direct election of the President and Vice President. This presidential election process would involve political parties nominating a presidential and vice-presidential ticket with the option of a runoff election.<ref>{{Cite news | last = Aglionby | first = John | title = Indonesia takes a giant step down the road to democracy | url = https://www.theguardian.com/world/2002/aug/11/indonesia.johnaglionby | work = [[The Observer]] | date = 11 August 2002 | accessdate =10 June 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Candidates==\n[[File:Indonesia presidential polls 2004.png|thumb|400px|A series of tracking surveys conducted by the [[International Foundation for Electoral Systems]] between December 2003 and late June 2004 showed the popularity of each presidential candidate among voters throughout the selection and campaign periods.<ref>{{Cite journal | title = Results from Wave XIV of Tracking Surveys | url = http://www.ifes.org/publication/45d5b9ab8e448881607d9cf731703fe8/2004_Tracking_Survey_Results_from_WaveXIV.pdf | publisher = [[International Foundation for Electoral Systems]] | format = PDF | page = 5 | date = 1 July 2004 | accessdate = 28 June 2009 | postscript = . | ref = harv | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20081129001443/http://www.ifes.org/publication/45d5b9ab8e448881607d9cf731703fe8/2004_Tracking_Survey_Results_from_WaveXIV.pdf | archive-date = 29 November 2008 | url-status = dead | df = dmy-all }}</ref>]]\nIn December 2003, the [[International Foundation for Electoral Systems]] (IFES) began a tracking survey in order to assess the popularity of potential candidates. The survey continued until the start of the first election round on 5 July and included thirteen possible candidates for President. The first IFES survey indicated that incumbent President [[Megawati Sukarnoputri]] received a plurality of the votes. However, by the time of the [[2004 Indonesian legislative election|April 2004 legislative election]], retired General [[Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono]] had taken the lead from Megawati after resigning from her cabinet in March. Other potential candidates included DPR Speaker [[Akbar Tanjung]] and [[Yogyakarta Sultanate|Yogyakarta Sultan]] [[Hamengkubuwana X]].<ref name=\"AAS 67-69\">{{Harvnb|Ananta|Arifin|Suryadinata|2005|pp=67\u201369|Ref=none}}</ref>\n\nThe results of the legislative election determined which political parties were eligible to submit presidential tickets. Only parties which received at least 5% of the popular vote or 3% of seats (17 of 550 seats) in the DPR would be allowed to submit candidates. Parties that did not meet these criteria must join with other parties to meet at least one criterion.  Seven political parties met these criteria: the [[Golkar|Party of the Functional Groups]] (Golkar), the [[Indonesian Democratic Party of Struggle]] (PDI-P), the [[National Awakening Party]] (PKB), the [[United Development Party]] (PPP), the [[Democratic Party (Indonesia)|Democratic Party]] (PD), the [[Prosperous Justice Party]] (PKS), and the [[National Mandate Party]] (PAN). The PKS was the only party not to nominate candidates, but it later threw its support behind the PAN.<ref name=\"AAS 70\">{{Harvnb|Ananta|Arifin|Suryadinata|2005|p=70|Ref=none}}</ref>\n\nThe KPU announced the final list of candidates on 14 May. Following the announcement, all candidates were required to undergo medical screening. On 22 May, the Commission announced that the PKB's presidential candidate, former President [[Abdurrahman Wahid]], had failed the eye test and was not allowed to enter in the election.<ref name=\"AAS 70\"/> He initially told supporters not to vote for a presidential candidate on election day but decided to retract that statement after pressure from the party.<ref>{{Cite news | title = Gus Dur Tuntut KPU Rp 1 Triliun | url = http://www.suaramerdeka.com/harian/0405/23/nas01.htm | work = [[Suara Merdeka]] | date = 23 May 2004 | language = Indonesian | accessdate = 21 June 2009 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110716162053/http://www.suaramerdeka.com/harian/0405/23/nas01.htm | archive-date = 16 July 2011 | url-status = dead | df = dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news | title = Gus Dur Batal Ajak Golput | url = http://www.suaramerdeka.com/harian/0405/24/pem01.htm | work = [[Suara Merdeka]] | date = 24 May 2004 | language = Indonesian | accessdate = 21 June 2009 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20070630101141/http://www.suaramerdeka.com/harian/0405/24/pem01.htm | archive-date = 30 June 2007 | url-status = dead | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Wiranto and Salahuddin Wahid===\n{{Main|Wiranto|Salahuddin Wahid}}\nGolkar had won the April legislative election after losing to the PDI\u2013P five years prior. The party nominated retired General Wiranto and Salahuddin Wahid, deputy chairman of the National Human Rights Commission, for its presidential ticket. The pair was assigned the number '''1''' for its ballot.<ref name=\"Ballot\">{{Cite news | title = 5 Pasang Capres-Cawapres Peroleh Nomor Urut | url = http://www2.kompas.com/kompas-cetak/0405/24/utama/1040214.htm | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20040618082422/http://www.kompas.com/kompas-cetak/0405/24/utama/1040214.htm | work = [[Kompas]] | date = 24 May 2004 | language = Indonesian | archivedate = 18 June 2004 | accessdate =10 September 2009}}</ref>\n\nWiranto was an [[adjutant]] to former President [[Suharto]] in 1989\u20131993. During this time, he rapidly rose to the rank of full general and eventually became the head of the [[Indonesian National Armed Forces|National Armed Forces]].<ref name=\"AAS 71\">{{Harvnb|Ananta|Arifin|Suryadinata|2005|p=71|Ref=none}}</ref> When riots broke out throughout the country in 1998 against Suharto, he refused to take control in order to avoid the deaths of protesting university students. In 1999, as [[East Timor]] held an independence referendum, Wiranto was accused of having taken part in inciting violence among East Timorese along with several other officers; however, he was never issued an arrest warrant by [[Interpol]].<ref name=\"CNN Wiranto\">{{Cite news | last = Chew | first = Amy | title = Wiranto emerges as 2004 contender | url = http://edition.cnn.com/2003/WORLD/asiapcf/southeast/12/19/indonesia.wiranto/ | publisher = [[CNN]] | date = 22 December 2003 | accessdate =21 June 2009}}</ref> Under President Abdurrahman Wahid, Wiranto served as the Coordinating Minister for Political and Security Affairs but was later dismissed. On 20 April 2004, the Golkar Convention voted to nominate him for President over DPR Speaker Akbar Tanjung in the second round of voting.<ref name=\"AAS 71\"/>\n\nOn 9 May, Golkar selected Salahuddin Wahid (also known as Gus Sholah) as its vice-presidential candidate after an endorsement was made by his brother Abdurrahman.<ref>{{Cite news | title = Golkar picks Gus Solah as VP candidate | url = http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2004/05/10/golkar-picks-gus-solah-vp-candidate.html | work = [[The Jakarta Post]] | date = 10 May 2004 | accessdate = 28 June 2009 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110607121810/http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2004/05/10/golkar-picks-gus-solah-vp-candidate.html | archivedate = 7 June 2011 | df = dmy-all }}</ref> Because Salahuddin was also a deputy chairman of the Central Board of [[Nahdlatul Ulama]], many NU members criticised him for not adhering to the organisation's ''khittah'', which affirmed the NU's status as a non-political organisation.<ref name=\"Khittah\">{{Cite book | last = Fealy | first = Greg | editor1-last = Reid | editor1-first = Anthony | editor1-link = Anthony Reid (academic) | editor2-last = Gilsenan | editor2-first = Michael | lastauthoramp = yes | title = Islamic Legitimacy in a Plural Asia | chapter = The political contingency of reform-mindedness in Indonesia's Nahdlatul Ulama: interest politics and the ''Khittah'' | publisher = Routledge | place = London | year = 2007 | page = 163 | isbn = 0-415-45173-6}}</ref> With this nomination, PKB leaders officially supported the Wiranto\u2013Salahuddin pair for the election.<ref name=\"AAS 71\"/>\n\nSalahuddin's position on the human rights commission helped the reputation of Wiranto. However, because both candidates were of [[Javanese people|Javanese]] background, they were not expected to attract as many voters who were not Javanese.<ref name=\"AAS 71\"/>\n\n===Megawati Sukarnoputri and Hasyim Muzadi===\n{{Main|Megawati Sukarnoputri|Hasyim Muzadi}}\nIncumbent President Megawati Sukarnoputri was the PDI\u2013P's top nominee. She was joined by vice-presidential candidate Hasyim Muzadi, general chairman of Indonesia's largest Islamic organisation Nahdlatul Ulama (NU). The pair was assigned the number '''2''' for its ballot.<ref name=\"Ballot\"/>\n\nAccording to a report released by the [[National Democratic Institute for International Affairs]], Megawati has a \"unique burden of being the only candidate in the race who is held responsible for the current situation most voters are unhappy with\" although several other candidates have been members of her government.<ref name=\"NDI\">{{Cite journal | title = The People's Voice: Presidential Politics and Voter Perspectives in Indonesia | url = http://www.ndi.org/files/1729_id_focusgroups.pdf | format = PDF | date = June 2004 | publisher = [[National Democratic Institute for International Affairs]] | accessdate = 28 June 2009 | postscript = . | ref = harv | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20081129125402/http://www.ndi.org/files/1729_id_focusgroups.pdf | archivedate = 29 November 2008 | df = dmy-all }}</ref> However, the general discontent for her presidency was attributed mainly to the failure of the government to communicate Megawati's achievements rather than the state of the country itself.<ref name=\"AAS 91\">{{Harvnb|Ananta|Arifin|Suryadinata|p=91|Ref=none}}</ref> The PDI\u2013P came in second during the April legislative election with 18.5% of the votes, a reduction by almost half from the 33.7% it had received in 1999.<ref name=\"AAS 22\">{{Harvnb|Ananta|Arifin|Suryadinata|2005|p=22|Ref=none}}</ref>\n\nHasyim Muzadi had been mentioned as a possible running mate for Megawati as early as November 2003.<ref>{{Cite news | last = Pereira | first = Derwin | title = Who will be Mega's running mate? | work = [[The Straits Times]] | date = 7 November 2003}}</ref> His candidacy was officially announced by Megawati on 6 May.<ref>{{Cite news | title = Megawati Memilih Hasyim Muzadi Sebagai Calon Wakil Presiden | url = http://www.voanews.com/indonesian/archive/2004-05/a-2004-05-06-10-1.cfm | publisher = [[Voice of America]] | date = 6 May 2004 | language = Indonesian | accessdate =28 June 2009}}</ref> As Chairman of the Central Board of Nahdlatul Ulama, he was criticised by many NU members for not adhering to the organisation's ''khittah'' and the principle of political neutrality.<ref name=\"Khittah\"/> Muslim intellectual [[Nurcholish Madjid]] had called on him to step down from the position following the announcement of the candidacy.<ref>{{Cite news | last = Arvian | first = Yandhrie | title = Cak Nur: Hasyim Muzadi Khianati Khitah NU | url = http://www.tempointeraktif.com/hg/nasional/2004/05/06/brk,20040506-23,id.html | work = [[Tempo magazine (Indonesia)|Tempo]] | date = 6 May 2004 | language = Indonesian | accessdate = 28 June 2009 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20080908052913/http://www.tempointeraktif.com/hg/nasional/2004/05/06/brk,20040506-23,id.html | archive-date = 8 September 2008 | url-status = dead | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe two candidates' Javanese background were not expected to attract as many non-Javanese voters.<ref name=\"AAS 71\"/> However, the candidates' status as civilians attracted those who did not favour candidates with a military background, and they also were expected to attract both secular and religious voters.<ref name=\"AAS 72\">{{Harvnb|Ananta|Arifin|Suryadinata|2005|p=72|Ref=none}}</ref>\n\n===Amien Rais and Siswono Yudohusodo===\n{{Main|Amien Rais|Siswono Yudohusodo}}\nThe PAN nominated Amien Rais, chairman of the MPR, as its presidential candidate. His running mate was Siswono Yudohusodo. The pair was assigned the number '''3''' for its ballot.<ref name=\"Ballot\"/>\n\nAmien Rais had once served as the chairman of [[Muhammadiyah]]. However, despite leading the second-largest Islamic organisation in Indonesia, Amien established the PAN following the resignation of President Suharto as a party not based on religious affiliation. He became an influential figure in the early days of the reform period and was eventually elected to lead the MPR.<ref name=\"AAS 12\">{{Harvnb|Ananta|Arifin|Suryadinata|2005|p=12|Ref=none}}</ref> Among voters, he was seen as a candidate who had no association with the [[Political corruption|corruption]] that was endemic to the nation's government. Voters also saw him as an ambitious person and as one who was known for being an [[orator]].<ref name=\"NDI\"/> Amien's party had received 6.4% of the votes during the legislative election.<ref name=\"AAS 22\"/>\n\nOn the other hand, Siswono Yudohusodo was a relative newcomer to the political scene. He served as the chairman of the Indonesian Farmers' Association (HKTI) and held ministerial positions during the later years of Suharto's presidency.<ref name=\"AAS 72\"/> Siswono was the wealthiest of any candidate for President or Vice President based on reports submitted by candidates to the [[Corruption Eradication Commission]].<ref>{{Cite news | last = Sri Saraswati | first = Muninggar | title = Siswono the richest, Amien poorest candidate | url = http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2004/07/03/siswono-richest-amien-poorest-candidate.html | work = [[The Jakarta Post]] | date = 3 July 2004 | accessdate = 29 June 2009 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110607121831/http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2004/07/03/siswono-richest-amien-poorest-candidate.html | archivedate = 7 June 2011 | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nLike Megawati and Hasyim, Amien and Siswono were also not expected to attract many non-Javanese voters. The pair was supported by the PKS, the seventh party which met the criteria to submit presidential and vice-presidential candidates but did not do so, and a number of smaller parties.<ref name=\"AAS 72\"/>\n\n===Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono and Jusuf Kalla===\n{{Main|Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono|Jusuf Kalla}}\n[[File:Yudhoyono campaign rally 2004.jpg|thumb|The rapid rise in Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono's (center) popularity helped the Democratic Party garner 7.45% of votes during the April 2004 legislative election.<ref name=\"AAS 56\">{{Harvnb|Ananta|Arifin|Suryadinata|2005|p=56|Ref=none}}</ref>]]\nThe Democratic Party, supported by the [[Indonesian Justice and Unity Party]] (PKPI) and [[Crescent Star Party (Indonesia)|Crescent Star Party]] (PBB), nominated retired General Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono for its presidential candidate. He was later joined by Jusuf Kalla as running mate, and the pair was assigned the number '''4''' for its ballot.<ref name=\"Ballot\"/>\n\nSusilo Bambang Yudhoyono has served in the cabinets of two previous administrations. While serving as Coordinating Minister for Political, Social and Security Affairs under Abdurrahman Wahid, he refused an order to declare a [[state of emergency]] that would have stopped the parliamentary process to impeach the President and was subsequently dismissed.<ref>{{Harvnb|Ricklefs|2008|p=395|Ref=none}}</ref> Yudhoyono was nominated for Vice President after the MPR selected Megawati to succeed Abdurrahman Wahid, but he lost the election to PPP Chairman Hamzah Haz and DPR Speaker Akbar Tanjung.<ref name=\"AAS 23\">{{Harvnb|Ananta|Arifin|Suryadinata|2005|p=23|Ref=none}}</ref> He reprised his prior cabinet position in Megawati's administration but resigned on 1 March 2004 to join the race for the presidency.<ref name=\"AAS 72\"/> The Democratic Party, established as a vehicle for Yudhoyono's political career by secular nationalists who saw the potential of his leadership,<ref name=\"AAS 23\"/> received 7.45% of votes and 10% of DPR seats in the April legislative election.<ref name=\"AAS 22\"/>\n\nYudhoyono's running mate was Jusuf Kalla, a wealthy [[Bugis]] businessman and member of Golkar who served as Coordinating Minister for People's Welfare under Megawati.<ref name=\"AAS 73\">{{Harvnb|Ananta|Arifin|Suryadinata|2005|p=73|Ref=none}}</ref> He mediated two separate peaceful resolutions to inter-religious conflicts between Christians and Muslims in his native [[Sulawesi]] in 2001 and [[Maluku Islands|Maluku]] in 2002.<ref>{{Cite news | last1 = Muannas | last2 = Amir | first2 = Syarief | title = Deklarasi Malino Mengakhiri Pertikaian di Poso | url = http://www.tempointeraktif.com/hg/nasional/2001/12/20/brk,20011220-26,id.html | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20041130232806/http://www.tempointeraktif.com/hg/nasional/2001/12/20/brk,20011220-26,id.html | url-status = dead | archive-date = 30 November 2004 | work = [[Tempo magazine (Indonesia)|Tempo]] | date = 20 December 2001 | language = Indonesian | accessdate = 10 September 2009 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite book | last = Hadi | first = Syamsul | title = Disintegrasi Pasca Orde Baru: Negara, Konflik Lokal dan Dinamika Internasional | language = Indonesian | page = 179 | publisher = Centre for International Relations Studies | place = Jakarta | year = 2007 | isbn = 979-461-624-9}}</ref> Kalla joined Golkar's selection process for the party's presidential nominee in August 2003 but withdrew his candidacy days before the party convention the following April.<ref>{{Cite news | title = Wiranto dan Kalla Maju, Agum Gumelar Mundur | url = http://www.kompas.com/kompas-cetak/0308/07/nasional/480103.htm | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20030808015457/http://www.kompas.com/kompas-cetak/0308/07/nasional/480103.htm | work = [[Kompas]] | date = 7 August 2003 | language = Indonesian | archivedate = 8 August 2003 | accessdate =10 September 2009}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news | title = Kalla Mundur Sebelum Konvensi | url = http://www.radarsulteng.com/berita/index.asp?Berita=Utama&id=30947 | work = Radar Sulteng | date = 16 April 2004 | language = Indonesian | accessdate = 10 September 2009 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20111008214105/http://www.radarsulteng.com/berita/index.asp?Berita=Utama&id=30947 | archive-date = 8 October 2011 | url-status = dead | df = dmy-all }}</ref> Several days later, he resigned his cabinet position and announced his alliance with Yudhoyono.<ref name=\"AAS 73\"/> Kalla was also seen as a potential vice-presidential candidate for the incumbent Megawati.<ref>{{Cite news | title = Blow to Megawati re-election bid | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/asia-pacific/3638903.stm | publisher = [[BBC]] | date = 19 April 2004 | accessdate =10 September 2009}}</ref>\n\nThe combination brought together two men with very different backgrounds that added to the attractiveness of their ticket. Yudhoyono, who was raised in densely populated Java, is seen as more secular and has a military background. On the other hand, Kalla is a devout Muslim who grew up in the outer province of South Sulawesi and came from a civilian background.<ref name=\"AAS 73\"/>\n\n===Hamzah Haz and Agum Gumelar===\n{{Main|Hamzah Haz|Agum Gumelar}}\nIncumbent Vice President Hamzah Haz was the presidential nominee of the PPP. He was joined by Minister of Transportation Agum Gumelar for the vice-presidential candidate. The pair was assigned the number '''5''' for its ballot.<ref name=\"Ballot\"/>\n\nHamzah Haz was elected Vice President by the MPR after defeating DPR Speaker Akbar Tanjung when it removed President Abdurrahman Wahid from office in 2001. Although the [[BBC]] reported him once stating that \"no woman was fit to head the world's leading Muslim nation\", he came into office as the deputy to Indonesia's first female president. Haz served in the cabinet of President [[B. J. Habibie]] and was the first minister to resign from the Abdurrahman Wahid administration. He was accused of [[Political corruption#Graft|graft]] and [[nepotism]] but was never subjected to an investigation.<ref>{{Cite news | title = Profile: Hamzah Haz | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/asia-pacific/1457865.stm | publisher = [[BBC]] | date = 26 July 2001 | accessdate =12 September 2009}}</ref> As Vice President, Haz had been a proponent of an amendment to the Constitution which would impose [[Sharia|Islamic law]] on Muslims in the country. However, other political parties and the Islamic organisations Nahdlatul Ulama and Muhammadiyah opposed such amendment for fear of more extreme forms of Islam.<ref>{{Harvnb|Ricklefs|2008|p=400|Ref=none}}</ref>\n\nA relatively unknown figure in the political scene, Agum Gumelar served as Minister of Transportation under Abdurrahman Wahid and Megawati.<ref name=\"AAS 73\"/> In September 2003, Agum had recommended Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono or Jusuf Kalla as Megawati's running mate in the presidential election after predicting that the PDI\u2013P would lose a significant number of votes in the April legislative election. However, both men eventually formed their own ticket, and Agum declined a vice-presidential candidate offer from Amien Rais in order to remain on the cabinet. He eventually accepted an offer from the PPP leadership to become Haz's running mate and resigned from Megawati's administration.<ref>{{Cite web | last1 = Cahyana | first1 = Ludhi | last2 = Parlan | first2 = Tri Mariyani | title = Hamzah Haz dan Agum Gumelar | url = http://www.isai.or.id/?q=node/20 | publisher = Institute for the Studies on Free Flow of Information | language = Indonesian | accessdate = 12 September 2009 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110721063726/http://www.isai.or.id/?q=node%2F20 | archivedate = 21 July 2011 | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nNeither candidate was of Javanese origin; hence, they might have attracted constituencies of the outer provinces.<ref name=\"AAS 73\"/>\n\n==Campaign==\n[[Political corruption|Corruption]], [[collusion]], and [[nepotism]] are the most consistently cited concerns among voters surveyed by the [[National Democratic Institute for International Affairs]].<ref name=\"NDI\"/>\n\n===Schedule===\n* 1 June 2004: All candidates sign the commitment of readiness to accept victory or defeat and to conduct a fair campaign.<ref name=\"Menang Kalah\">{{Cite news | title = Semua Calon Siap Menang dan Kalah | url = http://www2.kompas.com/kompas-cetak/0406/02/utama/1059733.htm | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20040622130535/http://www.kompas.com/kompas-cetak/0406/02/utama/1059733.htm | work = [[Kompas]] | date = 2 June 2004 | language = Indonesian | archivedate = 22 June 2004 | accessdate =10 September 2009}}</ref> Campaign period begins.<ref>{{Cite news | title = Jadwal Kampanye Pemilu Presiden | url = http://www.tempointeraktif.com/hg/narasi/2004/05/27/nrs,20040527-01,id.html | work = [[Tempo magazine (Indonesia)|Tempo]] | date = 27 May 2004 | language = Indonesian | accessdate = 21 June 2009 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20090623212306/http://www.tempointeraktif.com/hg/narasi/2004/05/27/nrs,20040527-01,id.html | archive-date = 23 June 2009 | url-status = dead | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n* 1 July 2004: Campaign period ends.\n* 5 July 2004: '''First round of voting'''.\n* 20 September 2004: '''Second round of voting'''.\n* 4 October 2004: Official second round results announced.<ref>{{Cite news | last = Purwanto | title = Presiden Terpilih Ditetapkan Sore Ini | url = http://www.tempointeraktif.com/hg/nasional/2004/10/04/brk,20041004-21,id.html | work = [[Tempo magazine (Indonesia)|Tempo]] | date = 4 October 2004 | language = Indonesian | accessdate = 21 June 2009 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20090614234242/http://www.tempointeraktif.com/hg/nasional/2004/10/04/brk,20041004-21,id.html | archive-date = 14 June 2009 | url-status = dead | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n* 20 October 2004: Inauguration of the President-elect and Vice President-elect.\n\n==Results==\nFormer security minister [[Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono]] won the first round with 33% of the vote. Incumbent President [[Megawati Sukarnoputri]] was second with 26%, ahead of former armed forces chief [[Wiranto]] on 22%. Yudhoyono did not do as well as earlier opinion polls had suggested, while Megawati did better. This was attributed by Indonesian observers to Yudhoyono's lack of a nationwide party machine, such as Megawati's PDI-P and Wiranto's Golkar.{{Citation needed|date=June 2009}}\n\nThe counting of 113 million votes, already a massive task in such a large and diverse country, was made more difficult by problems with the ballot papers.  Voters cast their ballots by making a hole in the ballot paper with a nail, above the photo of their preferred candidate. Because the ballot paper was handed to voters folded in half, many made the hole without unfolding the ballot, thus making two holes and invalidating their vote. Hundreds of thousands of these votes were invalidated before the General Election Committee (KPU) ruled that such ballots should be accepted.<ref>{{Cite news | last = Harsono | first = Andreas | title = Megawati Crawls In While Wiranto Cries Foul | url = http://www.irrawaddy.org/article.php?art_id=3657 | work = [[The Irrawaddy]] | date = 8 July 2004 | accessdate = 21 June 2009 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20100811195324/http://irrawaddy.org/article.php?art_id=3657 | archivedate = 11 August 2010 | df = dmy-all }}</ref> This necessitated recounts in many places, slowing the count and raising fears of a disputed result.\n{{electiontable|Indonesian presidential election, 2004|editlink=no}}\nSummary of the 5 July and 20 September 2004 [[Indonesia]]n presidential election results\n|-\n! style=\"background-color:#E9E9E9;text-align:left;\" rowspan=2 |Candidate\n! style=\"background-color:#E9E9E9;text-align:left;\" rowspan=2 |Running mate\n! style=\"background-color:#E9E9E9;text-align:left;\" rowspan=2 |Party\n! style=\"background-color:#E9E9E9;text-align:center;\" colspan=2 |First round\n! style=\"background-color:#E9E9E9;text-align:center;\" colspan=2 |Second round\n|-\n! style=\"background-color:#E9E9E9;text-align:center;\" |Votes\n! style=\"background-color:#E9E9E9;text-align:center;\" |%\n! style=\"background-color:#E9E9E9;text-align:center;\" |Votes\n! style=\"background-color:#E9E9E9;text-align:center;\" |%\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | '''[[Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono]]'''\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | '''[[Jusuf Kalla]]'''\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |'''[[Democratic Party (Indonesia)|Democratic Party]]''' (''Partai Demokrat'')\n|'''39,838,184'''\n|'''33.57'''\n|'''69,266,350'''\n|'''60.62'''\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | '''[[Megawati Sukarnoputri]]'''\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | '''[[Hasyim Muzadi]]'''\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |'''[[Indonesian Democratic Party \u2013 Struggle]]''' (''Partai Demokrasi Indonesia Perjuangan'')\n|'''31,569,104'''\n|'''26.61'''\n|44,990,704\n|39.38\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Wiranto]]\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Salahuddin Wahid]]\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Golongan Karya|Party of the Functional Groups]] (''Partai Golongan Karya'')\n|26,286,788\n|22.15\n|style=\"background-color:#E9E9E9\" colspan=2 rowspan=3| \n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Amien Rais]]\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Siswono Yudohusodo]]\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[National Mandate Party]] (''Partai Amanat Nasional'')\n|17,392,931\n|14.66\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Hamzah Haz]]\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Agum Gumelar]]\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[United Development Party]] (''Partai Persatuan Pembangunan'')\n|3,569,861\n|3.01\n|-\n|style=\"background-color:#E9E9E9\" colspan=7|\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" colspan=3 |'''Total'''\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" |'''118,656,868'''\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" |100.00\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" |'''114,257,054'''\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" |100.00\n|-\n| colspan=7 style=\"text-align:left;\" |Source: {{Harvnb|Ananta|Arifin|Suryadinata|2005|pp=80\u201383, 107}}\n|}\n\n===First round===\n[[File:Map of 2004 Indonesian Presidential Election (1st Round) - Provinces.svg|thumb|600px|center|Results of the first round: the candidate with the majority of votes in each of the 32 [[provinces of Indonesia]].<ref>Compiled from {{Harvnb|Ananta|Arifin|Suryadinata|2005|Ref=none}}, table 3.3</ref><br/>Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono: <span style=\"color:#191970;\">dark blue</span>; Megawati Sukarnoputri: <span style=\"color:#8b0000;\">red</span>; Wiranto: <span style=\"color:yellow;\">yellow</span>; Amien Rais: <span style=\"color:#9ec7f3;\">light blue</span>.]]\nWiranto refused to accept the election results and petitioned the [[Indonesian Constitutional Court|Constitutional Court]]. Wiranto and Salahuddin argued that, due to irregularities in ballot counting by the KPU, they had lost 5,434,660 votes from twenty-six provinces. Those ballots would have made the total popular vote for the pair higher than that for Megawati and Hasyim, putting the former pair instead of the latter in the second round. However, the Court ruled on 10 August that it found no irregularities and upheld the Commission's final count.<ref>{{Harvnb|Ananta|Arifin|Suryadinata|2005|p=69|Ref=none}}</ref>\n\n====Analysis====\n\n===Second round===\n[[File:Map of 2004 Indonesian Presidential Election (2nd Round) - Provinces.svg|thumb|600px|center|Results of the second round: the candidate with the majority of votes in each of the 32 [[provinces of Indonesia]].<ref>Compiled from {{Harvnb|Ananta|Arifin|Suryadinata|2005|Ref=none}}, table 4.3</ref><br/>Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono: <span style=\"color:#191970;\">dark blue</span>; Megawati Sukarnoputri: <span style=\"color:#8b0000;\">red</span>.]]\n\n====Analysis====\n\n==Reactions==\n*'''[[Indonesia]]:''' President [[Megawati Sukarnoputri]] said in a speech on Armed Forces Day, 5 October, \"We have to show to the world we are a big nation. All components of the nation have to stick to the agreement we have struck that whoever is elected in the democratic election has to be accepted. We may have chosen differently. However, we had the same objective: that is to bring the nation to a better future.\"<ref>{{Cite news | last = Moore | first = Matthew | title = Megawati still keeping Yudhoyono on hold | url = http://www.smh.com.au/articles/2004/10/05/1096949513009.html | work = [[The Sydney Morning Herald]] | publisher = [[Fairfax Media]] | date = 6 October 2004 | accessdate =20 June 2009}}</ref>\n*'''[[Australia]]''': Prime Minister [[John Howard]] planned to attend Yudhoyono's inauguration. Howard said, \"I look forward to working closely with Dr. Yudhoyono and his new government to continue and extend the close cooperation between our two nations, particularly on counter-terrorism.\"<ref>{{Cite news | last = Forbes | first = Mark | title = PM to see new leader sworn in | url = http://www.theage.com.au/articles/2004/10/14/1097607368339.html | newspaper = [[The Age]] | publisher = [[Fairfax Media]] | date = 15 October 2004 | accessdate =20 June 2009}}</ref>\n*'''[[People's Republic of China]]''': [[Politburo Standing Committee of the Communist Party of China|Politburo Standing Committee]] member [[Wu Guanzheng]] met with Yudhoyono on 13 October and conveyed congratulations from President [[Hu Jintao]].<ref>{{Cite news | title = Senior Chinese leader meets Indonesia's president-elect | url = http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2004-10/15/content_2091733.htm | agency = [[Xinhua News Agency]] | date = 14 October 2004 | accessdate =20 June 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Aftermath==\n{{Wikinews|Indonesia's president visits victims of tsunami}}\n[[Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono]] and [[Jusuf Kalla]] were sworn in as President and Vice President on 20 October. It was the first Indonesian presidential inauguration to be attended by foreign leaders.<ref>{{Harvnb|Ananta|Arifin|Suryadinata|2005|p=121|Ref=none}}</ref> After a selection process that began on 15 October, the [[United Indonesia Cabinet]] was announced later following the inauguration. The 36-member cabinet was sworn in at the [[Istana Negara, Jakarta|State Palace]] on 21 October.<ref>{{Harvnb|Ananta|Arifin|Suryadinata|2005|p=128|Ref=none}}</ref> The process of selecting candidates for Yudhoyono's cabinet was considered \"decent, intelligent, and indecisive\". While attempting to satisfy as many members as possible in his coalition of small parties, Yudhoyono created a cabinet that was neither quite as cohesive nor effective. However, Kalla soon became the party chairman of Golkar in late 2004 and turned the party's votes in the DPR to those in favour of the government, creating an effective ''bloc'' and leaving Megawati's PDI\u2013P as the largest non-government party in the DPR.<ref>{{Harvnb|Ricklefs|2008|pp=404\u2013405|Ref=none}}</ref> Although the first one hundred days of Yudhoyono's administration saw continuing economic stability, it was overshadowed by the events of the [[2004 Indian Ocean earthquake|Indian Ocean earthquake]] which occurred on 26 December. The earthquake triggered [[tsunami]]s that destroyed the coastline of the provinces of [[Aceh]] and [[North Sumatra]] and killed more than 200,000 people.<ref>{{Harvnb|Ananta|Arifin|Suryadinata|2005|pp=132\u2013133|Ref=none}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Indonesia}}\n* [[Elections in Indonesia]]\n* [[2004 Indonesian legislative election]]\n* [[Two-round system]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==References==\n* {{Cite book | last1 = Ananta | first1 = Aris | last2 = Arifin | first2 = Evi Nurvidya | last3 = Suryadinata | first3 = Leo | lastauthoramp = yes | title = Emerging Democracy in Indonesia | place = Singapore | publisher = Institute of Southeast Asian Studies | year = 2005 | isbn = 978-981-230-322-6 | postscript = . | ref = harv}}\n* {{Cite book |first=Bob S. |last=Hadiwinata |title=The 2004 Parliamentary and Presidential Elections in Indonesia |work=Between Consolidation and Crisis: Elections and Democracy in Five Nations in Southeast Asia |publisher=Lit |place=Berlin |year=2006 |pages=85\u2013146}}\n* {{Cite book | last = Koirudin | title = Kilas Balik Pemilihan Presiden 2004 | place = Yogyakarta | publisher = Pustaka Pelajar | year = 2004 | language = Indonesian | isbn = 979-3721-11-1 | postscript = . | ref = harv}}\n* {{Cite book | last = Ricklefs | first = M. C. | authorlink = M. C. Ricklefs | title = A History of Modern Indonesia since c. 1200 | year = 2008 | publisher = Stanford University Press | place = Stanford, CA | edition = 4th | isbn = 0-8047-6130-2 | postscript = . | ref = harv}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.kpu.go.id General Election Commission]\n\n{{Indonesian elections}}\n\n[[Category:2004 elections in Asia]]\n[[Category:2004 in Indonesia|Presidential election]]\n[[Category:Presidential elections in Indonesia|2004]]\n", "name_user": "Chris the speller", "label": "safe", "comment": "cap", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2004_Indonesian_presidential_election"}
{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in Nova Scotia", "text_new": "{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in Nova Scotia}}\n{{Use Canadian English|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| first_case      = \n| confirmed_cases = 549, as of April 15<ref name=\"novascotia1\">{{cite press release|url=https://novascotia.ca/news/release/?id=20200415002|title=Thirty-two New Cases of COVID-19|publisher=Government of Nova Scotia, Canada |website=Novascotia.ca |date=2020-04-15|accessdate=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n| deaths          = 3, as of April 15<ref name=\"novascotia1\"/>\n| recovery_cases  = 137, as of April 15<ref name=\"novascotia1\"/>\n| website         = [https://novascotia.ca/coronavirus/ Nova Scotia Government]\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Nova Scotia\n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| origin          = [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei]], [[China]]\n| arrival_date    = March 15, 2020<ref name=\"novascotia2\">{{cite press release |url=https://novascotia.ca/news/release/?id=20200315002 |title=First Presumptive Cases of COVID-19 in Nova Scotia; New Prevention Measures |publisher=Government of Nova Scotia, Canada |website=Novascotia.ca|access-date=March 23, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318085456/https://novascotia.ca/news/release/?id=20200315002 |archive-date=March 18, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> <br />({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=03|day1=11|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| location        = [[Nova Scotia]], [[Canada]]\n}}\nThe '''2020 coronavirus pandemic in Nova Scotia''' is an ongoing viral pandemic of [[coronavirus disease 2019]] (COVID-19), a novel infectious disease caused by [[severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2]] (SARS-CoV-2). {{As of|2020|04|14|df=US}}, the [[Canada|Canadian]] province of [[Nova Scotia]] has the fifth-most number of cases of [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Canada|COVID-19 in Canada]] during the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|2019\u201320 worldwide pandemic]]. {{As of|2020|04|14|df=US}}, there have been 549 confirmed cases, 137 recoveries, three deaths, and 17,419 negative tests.<ref name=\"novascotia1\"/><ref name=\"coronavirus/#cases\"/>\n__TOC__\n\n== Timeline ==\n<onlyinclude>\n{{Medical cases chart\n|barwidth=medium\n|numwidth=tw\n\n|disease=COVID-19\n|location=Nova Scotia\n|outbreak=2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic\n\n|togglesbar=\n<div class=\"nomobile\" style=\"text-align:center\">\n{{Medical cases chart/Month toggle button|mar}}\n{{Medical cases chart/Month toggle button|apr}}\n<span class=\"mw-collapsible mw-customtoggle-l15 mw-customtoggle-mar-l15 mw-collapsed\" id=\"mw-customcollapsible-l15\" style=\"padding:0 8px\">Last 15 days</span>\n<span class=\"mw-collapsible mw-customtoggle-l15 mw-customtoggle-mar-l15\" id=\"mw-customcollapsible-l15\" style=\"border:2px solid lightblue; padding:0 8px\">Last 15 days</span>\n</div>\n|rows=\n{{Medical cases chart/Row|2020-03-15|||3|||3|firstright1=y|divisor=1.8|numwidth=tw|collapsible=y}}\n{{Medical cases chart/Row|2020-03-16|||5|||5|+67%|divisor=1.8|numwidth=tw|collapsible=y}}\n{{Medical cases chart/Row|2020-03-17|||7|||7|+40%|divisor=1.8|numwidth=tw|collapsible=y}}\n{{Medical cases chart/Row|2020-03-18|||12|||12|+71%|divisor=1.8|numwidth=tw|collapsible=y}}\n{{Medical cases chart/Row|2020-03-19|||14|||14|+17%|divisor=1.8|numwidth=tw|collapsible=y}}\n{{Medical cases chart/Row|2020-03-20|||15|||15|+7.1%|divisor=1.8|numwidth=tw|collapsible=y}}\n{{Medical cases chart/Row|2020-03-21|||21|||21|+40%|divisor=1.8|numwidth=tw|collapsible=y}}\n{{Medical cases chart/Row|2020-03-22|||28|||28|+33%|divisor=1.8|numwidth=tw|collapsible=y}}\n{{Medical cases chart/Row|2020-03-23|||41|||41|+46%|divisor=1.8|numwidth=tw|collapsible=y}}\n{{Medical cases chart/Row|2020-03-24||1|51|||51|+24%|divisor=1.8|numwidth=tw|collapsible=y}}\n{{Medical cases chart/Row|2020-03-25||2|68|||68|+33%|divisor=1.8|numwidth=tw|collapsible=y}}\n{{Medical cases chart/Row|2020-03-26||2|73|||73|+7.3%|divisor=1.8|numwidth=tw|collapsible=y}}\n{{Medical cases chart/Row|2020-03-27||3|90|||90|+23%|divisor=1.8|numwidth=tw|collapsible=y}}\n{{Medical cases chart/Row|2020-03-28||4|110|||110|+22%|divisor=1.8|numwidth=tw|collapsible=y}}\n{{Medical cases chart/Row|2020-03-29||7|122|||122|+11%|divisor=1.8|numwidth=tw|collapsible=y}}\n{{Medical cases chart/Row|2020-03-30||10|127|||127|+4.1%|divisor=1.8|numwidth=tw|collapsible=y}}\n{{Medical cases chart/Row|2020-03-31||10|147|||147|+16%|divisor=1.8|numwidth=tw|collapsible=y}}\n{{Medical cases chart/Row|2020-04-01||11|173|||173|+18%|divisor=1.8|numwidth=tw|collapsible=y}}\n{{Medical cases chart/Row|2020-04-02||16|193|||193|+12%|divisor=1.8|numwidth=tw|collapsible=y}}\n{{Medical cases chart/Row|2020-04-03||21|207|||207|+7.2%|divisor=1.8|numwidth=tw|collapsible=y}}\n{{Medical cases chart/Row|2020-04-04||50|236|||236|+14%|divisor=1.8|numwidth=tw|collapsible=y}}\n{{Medical cases chart/Row|2020-04-05||53|262|||262|+11%|divisor=1.8|numwidth=tw|collapsible=y}}\n{{Medical cases chart/Row|2020-04-06||64|293|||293|+12%|divisor=1.8|numwidth=tw|collapsible=y}}\n{{Medical cases chart/Row|2020-04-07|1|66|310|||310|+5.8%|divisor=1.8|numwidth=tw|collapsible=y}}\n{{Medical cases chart/Row|2020-04-08|1|77|342|||342|+10%|divisor=1.8|numwidth=tw|collapsible=y}}\n{{Medical cases chart/Row|2020-04-09|2|82|373|||373|+9.1%|divisor=1.8|numwidth=tw|collapsible=y}}\n{{Medical cases chart/Row|2020-04-10|2|93|407|||407|+9.1%|divisor=1.8|numwidth=tw|collapsible=y}}\n{{Medical cases chart/Row|2020-04-11|2|95|428|||428|+5.2%|divisor=1.8|numwidth=tw|collapsible=y}}\n{{Medical cases chart/Row|2020-04-12|2|97|445|||445|+4.0%|divisor=1.8|numwidth=tw|collapsible=y}}\n{{Medical cases chart/Row|2020-04-13|3|101|473|||473|+6.3%|divisor=1.8|numwidth=tw|collapsible=y}}\n{{Medical cases chart/Row|2020-04-14|3|124|517|||517|+9.3%|divisor=1.8|numwidth=tw|collapsible=y}}\n{{Medical cases chart/Row|2020-04-15|3|137|549|||549|+6.2%|divisor=1.8|numwidth=tw|collapsible=y}}\n\n|caption='''Source:'''<ref name=\"coronavirus/#cases\">{{cite web|url=https://novascotia.ca/coronavirus/#cases |title=Novel coronavirus (COVID-19): COVID-19 testing data |publisher=Government of Nova Scotia, Canada |website=Novascotia.ca |date= |accessdate=2020-04-11|url-status=live}}</ref>\n}}</onlyinclude>\n\nOn March 15, Nova Scotia's first three presumptive cases were detected, all travel-related. Respectively, these cases were a woman in her 60s from [[Kings County, Nova Scotia|Kings County]] who visited [[Australia]] and returned March 8, a man in his late 50s from the [[Halifax, Nova Scotia|Halifax]] area who attended a conference in [[California]] and returned March 13, and a man in his 30s from the [[Halifax, Nova Scotia|Halifax]] area who travelled \"throughout Europe\" and returned March 10.<ref name=\"novascotia2\"/>\n\nOn March 16, two additional cases were reported. A man and a woman in their 50s from the [[Halifax Regional Municipality]] had not traveled, but had been in \"close contact with individuals who had recently travelled outside the country.\"<ref name=\"novascotia3\">{{cite press release|url=https://novascotia.ca/news/release/?id=20200316001 |title=Two New Presumptive Cases of COVID-19 in Nova Scotia |publisher=Government of Nova Scotia, Canada |website=Novascotia.ca |date=2020-03-16 |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\nOn March 17, Chief Medical Officer of Health Dr. Robert Strang announced that the reporting of information about individual cases would cease in order to protect patient privacy, as well as to prevent a false sense of security in communities without detected cases.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Coronavirus: N.S. limits public gatherings to 50 people as case numbers grow|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6689497/tuesday-coronavirus-update/|last=Benjamin|first=Graeme|date=March 17, 2020|access-date=March 23, 2020|url-status=live|work=Global News|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322191330/https://globalnews.ca/news/6689497/tuesday-coronavirus-update/|archive-date=March 22, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"novascotia4\">{{cite press release|url=https://novascotia.ca/news/release/?id=20200317001 |title=New Presumptive Cases of COVID-19 in Nova Scotia |publisher=Government of Nova Scotia, Canada |website=Novascotia.ca |date=2020-03-17 |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\nOn March 22, a provincial state of emergency was declared. It was also announced that the [[QEII Health Sciences Center|QEII Health Sciences Centre's Microbiology Lab]] in [[Halifax, Nova Scotia|Halifax]] was certified to report positive and negative tests for COVID-19, thus cases could be confirmed within the province, without needing to send samples to the [[National Microbiology Laboratory|National Microbiology Lab]] for confirmation.<ref name=\"novascotia5\">{{cite press release|url=https://novascotia.ca/news/release/?id=20200322001 |title=State of Emergency Declared in Response to COVID-19, Seven New Cases |publisher=Government of Nova Scotia, Canada |website=Novascotia.ca |access-date=March 23, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323151542/https://novascotia.ca/news/release/?id=20200322001 |archive-date=March 23, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn March 23, it was reported that at least one of the new cases was a child under age 10.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Coronavirus: Nova Scotia now has 41 cases, including at least one child under 10|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6717912/13-new-cases-ns/|last=Benjamin|first=Graeme|date=March 23, 2020|access-date=March 25, 2020|url-status=live|work=Global News}}</ref>\n\nOn March 30, Chief Medical Officer of Health Dr. Robert Strang announced the first official case of community spread, per the government definition of a case that can not be connected to travel or a previously known case.<ref name=\"novascotia6\">{{cite press release|url=https://novascotia.ca/news/release/?id=20200330003 |title=Five New Cases of COVID-19 in Nova Scotia |publisher=Government of Nova Scotia, Canada |website=Novascotia.ca |date=2020-03-30 |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\nOn March 31, it was reported that cases had been identified in four staff members and two residents of long-term care facilities for seniors.<ref name=\"novascotia7\">{{cite press release|url=https://novascotia.ca/news/release/?id=20200331001 |title=Twenty New Cases of COVID-19 in Nova Scotia |publisher=Government of Nova Scotia, Canada |website=Novascotia.ca |date=2020-03-31 |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\nOn April 7, the province reported its first death, a [[Cape Breton]] woman in her 70s with underlying medical conditions.<ref>{{cite web |title=Cape Breton woman in her 70s is Nova Scotia's first death related to COVID-19 |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/covid-19-death-nova-scotia-1.5524447 |website=CBC.ca |publisher=CBC News |date=April 7, 2020|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn April 9, the province reported its second death, a [[Cape Breton]] woman in her 90s with underlying medical conditions.<ref>{{cite web |title=Second death related to COVID-19 confirmed in Nova Scotia|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/second-covid-19-death-1.5527637|website=CBC.ca |publisher=CBC News |date=April 9, 2020|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Government response ==\nOn February 28, the Nova Scotia Human Rights Commission issued a press release in which Nova Scotians were \"asked to be vigilant against discrimination based on ethnic or national origin\" and cautioned that the \"Nova Scotia Human Rights Act protects against discrimination based on an irrational fear of contracting an illness or disease.\"<ref>{{cite press release|url=https://novascotia.ca/news/release/?id=20200228007 |title= COVID-19 and Discrimination |publisher=Government of Nova Scotia, Canada |website=Novascotia.ca |access-date=March 23, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303231557/https://novascotia.ca/news/release/?id=20200228007 |archive-date=March 3, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn March 4, Nova Scotia school trips to international destinations were cancelled.<ref>{{cite press release|url=https://novascotia.ca/news/release/?id=20200304005 |title=School Organized Trips to International Destinations Cancelled |publisher=Government of Nova Scotia, Canada |website=Novascotia.ca |date=2020-03-04 |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\nOn March 6, the provincial government announced that preparations for the virus were \"well underway,\" including the implementation of a patient screening process for healthcare workers, monitoring and investigation of potential cases, application of public health and infection control measures, and work with the Nova Scotia's Emergency Management Office.<ref>{{cite press release|url=https://novascotia.ca/news/release/?id=20200306003 |title=Coronavirus Preparations Well Underway |publisher=Government of Nova Scotia, Canada |website=Novascotia.ca |date= |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\nOn March 9, new national screening protocols were implemented in which those who had travelled outside Canada were requested to monitor for symptoms for 14 days, and those who began to feel unwell were requested to stay home and self-isolate from the public. Those who developed a fever of 38&nbsp;\u00b0C or higher and/or cough were requested to contact the health information line at 811 for assessment. Hygiene directives in regards to proper handwashing and cough etiquette were also issued.<ref>{{cite press release|url=https://novascotia.ca/news/release/?id=20200309002 |title=New National Screening Protocols for COVID-19 |publisher=Government of Nova Scotia, Canada |website=Novascotia.ca |date= |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\nOn March 13, all Nova Scotia public sector employees who travelled outside Canada were required to self-isolate for 14 days upon return.<ref>{{cite press release|url=https://novascotia.ca/news/release/?id=20200313002 |title=New Travel Measures for Nova Scotia Public Sector Employees |publisher=Government of Nova Scotia, Canada |website=Novascotia.ca |access-date=March 23, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318085459/https://novascotia.ca/news/release/?id=20200313002 |archive-date=March 18, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Additionally, Nova Scotia museums and art galleries were closed.<ref>{{cite press release|url=https://novascotia.ca/news/release/?id=20200313009 |title=Nova Scotia Museum Sites, Art Gallery of Nova Scotia Closed |publisher=Government of Nova Scotia, Canada |website=Novascotia.ca |date=2020-03-13 |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\nOn March 14, the Shubenacadie Wildlife Park was closed.<ref>{{cite press release|url=https://novascotia.ca/news/release/?id=20200314001 |title=Shubenacadie Wildlife Park to Close |publisher=Government of Nova Scotia, Canada |website=Novascotia.ca |date=2020-03-14 |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref> Additionally, Nova Scotia correctional facilities were closed to volunteer organizations, and inmates were limited to non-contact visitation by family and friends, meaning separation by a pane of glass and communication via a phone line. Inmates were also granted two free phone calls per week. There was no change in protocol for visitation by lawyers.<ref>{{cite press release|url=https://novascotia.ca/news/release/?id=20200314002 |title=Changes to Correctional Facilities Visits to Prevent COVID-19 |publisher=Government of Nova Scotia, Canada |website=Novascotia.ca |date=2020-03-14 |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\nOn March 15, provincial visitor information centres for tourists were closed, and the call centre responsible for fielding inquiries from tourists was also shuttered.<ref>{{cite press release|url=https://novascotia.ca/news/release/?id=20200315001 |title=Provincial Visitor Information Centres to Close Until Further Notice |publisher=Government of Nova Scotia, Canada |website=Novascotia.ca |date=2020-03-15 |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref> Additionally, long-term care facilities were closed to visitors, public schools were shut for two weeks from March 23 following March Break (subject to reassessment and extension), day cares were closed, March Break camps were cancelled, casinos were closed, bar owners were no longer allowed to operate video lottery terminals (VLTs), everyone who travelled outside Canada was asked to self-isolate regardless of the development of symptoms, social distancing of two metres was recommended, and gatherings were restricted to 150 \"or much smaller if possible.\"<ref name=\"novascotia2\"/> Further, all visitation to correctional facilities was suspended and lawyers were asked to arrange alternative means of maintaining contact with clients. Inmates were granted extra phone calls. Correctional Services also closed its facilities to all visitors until further notice.<ref>{{cite press release|url=https://novascotia.ca/news/release/?id=20200315004 |title=All Visits to Correctional Facilities Suspended to Prevent COVID-19 |publisher=Government of Nova Scotia, Canada |website=Novascotia.ca |date=2020-03-15 |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\nOn March 16, Nova Scotians were directed to first complete an online screening questionnaire before calling the 811 hotline due to an overwhelming influx of calls.<ref name=\"novascotia3\"/> Additionally, the government of Nova Scotia issued a warning about ongoing investment scams, with individuals impersonating banks over the phone.<ref>{{cite press release|author=Stephanie Atkinson |url=https://novascotia.ca/news/release/?id=20200316003 |title=Warning About COVID-19 Investment Scams |publisher=Government of Nova Scotia, Canada |website=Novascotia.ca |date=2020-03-16 |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\nOn March 17, Access Nova Scotia and offices of the Registry of Motor Vehicles were closed. Driver licences and vehicle registrations expiring in March, April and May were extended to August 31.<ref>{{cite press release|url=https://novascotia.ca/news/release/?id=20200317003 |title=Closure of Access Nova Scotia and Registry of Motor Vehicle Offices, Deadline Extension |publisher=Government of Nova Scotia, Canada |website=Novascotia.ca |date=2020-03-17 |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref> Additionally, bars were ordered closed, restaurants were limited to take-out and delivery only, and public gatherings were limited to 50 or fewer.<ref>{{cite press release|url=https://novascotia.ca/news/release/?id=20200317005 |title=Province\u2019s Bars to Close, Restaurants Limited to Take-out, Delivery as of Thursday; Gatherings Limited to 50 or Fewer Effective Immediately |publisher=Government of Nova Scotia, Canada |website=Novascotia.ca |date=2020-03-17 |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\nOn March 18, a number of new measures were announced to combat the spread of the virus. Doctors and pharmacists were granted expanded options for virtual care using telephone and video conference, pharmacists were allowed to renew prescriptions for most medications, employers were no longer allowed to require a doctor's note from employees seeking to take time off work, nurses were called from retirement to staff the 811 hotline, and service providers funded through the Department of Community Services\u2019 Disability Support Program were shuttered. A number of other services such as barber shops, tattoo shops, nail salons, and gyms were also ordered closed effective midnight March 19.<ref>{{cite press release|url=https://novascotia.ca/news/release/?id=20200318004 |title=New Restrictions; Province, Health System Working to Increase Capacity |publisher=Government of Nova Scotia, Canada |website=Novascotia.ca |date=2020-03-18 |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref> Additionally, 41 inmates serving intermittent sentences in four adult correctional facilities were released on temporary absence.<ref>{{cite press release|url=https://novascotia.ca/news/release/?id=20200318003 |title=Correctional Facilities Take Further Acton to Prevent Covid-19 |publisher=Government of Nova Scotia, Canada |website=Novascotia.ca |date=2020-03-18 |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\nOn March 19, Premier Stephen McNeil announced the allocation of $2.2 million for an increase of $50 to every individual and family member on income assistance, $1 million to the Feed Nova Scotia food bank, a three-month suspension of evictions, emergency funding of $230,000 for Senior Safety Programs and Community Links, as well as an order for university students still living in residence to go home, and for those university students unable to return home to practice social distancing.<ref>{{cite press release|url=https://novascotia.ca/news/release/?id=20200319004 |title=Measures to Help Vulnerable Nova Scotians |publisher=Government of Nova Scotia, Canada |website=Novascotia.ca |date=2020-03-19 |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\nOn March 20, the provincial government announced an allocation of $161 million for cash flow and credit access for small and medium Nova Scotia businesses. Payments on many government loans to businesses were deferred until June 30, and payments on Nova Scotia student loans were suspended until September 30. The government also allocated $15 million as an incentive for internet service providers to expand internet infrastructure.<ref>{{cite press release|url=https://novascotia.ca/news/release/?id=20200320003 |title=Measures to Help Nova Scotia Businesses, Students |publisher=Government of Nova Scotia, Canada |website=Novascotia.ca |date=2020-03-20 |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\nOn March 21, a number of health measures were announced, including the restriction of visitors to hospitals and the opening of new assessment centres, of which there 14 at the time.<ref name=\"novascotia8\">{{cite press release|url=https://novascotia.ca/news/release/?id=20200321001 |title=Six New Cases of COVID-19 in Nova Scotia |publisher=Government of Nova Scotia, Canada |website=Novascotia.ca |date=2020-03-21 |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\nOn March 22, the province of Nova Scotia declared a state of emergency. In accordance with the emergency declaration, land sea, and air points of entry were tightened, with anyone entering the province stopped, questioned, and told to self-isolate for 14 days, starting March 23. All provincial parks, beaches, and tourist attractions were closed, although provincial trails were left open for exercise. Police were authorized to enforce orders under the Health Protection Act, as well as the Emergency Management Act. Gatherings over 5 people were prohibited. Non-essential businesses were only allowed to remain open as long as a two-metre distance can be maintained. Dentists were no longer allowed to practice in their offices except in emergency circumstances.<ref name=\"novascotia5\"/>\n\nOn March 24, a series of new public health measures were announced, including the testing of all close contacts of positive cases, doubled lab capacity for viral testing, increased capacity for the 811 hotline, enhancement of infectious disease control measures in hospitals, restriction of regulated health professions to virtual care except for emergency or urgent cases, all non-regulated health professions closed, and the reopening of Access Nova Scotia Centres and Registry of Motor Vehicle Offices on a limited, reduced contact basis. Economic sectors deemed essential services and therefore exempt from gathering limitations were defined.<ref>{{cite press release|url=https://novascotia.ca/news/release/?id=20200324003 |title=Strengthening Health System and New Measures |publisher=Government of Nova Scotia, Canada |website=Novascotia.ca |date=2020-03-24 |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\nOn March 26, qualifying criteria for viral testing was expanded beyond travel-related cases to include anyone referred to an assessment centre by the 811 system, all close contacts of confirmed cases, and people in hospital who meet testing criteria. An alternative hotline for sick medical staff was also established in response to an overburdened 811 system. Additionally, camping reservations were put on hold and open fires were banned within 305 metres of woods throughout the province.<ref>{{cite press release|url=https://novascotia.ca/news/release/?id=20200326003 |title=Testing for COVID-19 Expands; Health System Preparations |publisher=Government of Nova Scotia, Canada |website=Novascotia.ca |date=2020-03-26 |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\nOn March 29, a Halifax woman was fined $697.50, and had her vehicle seized by police after she was found in a park despite Nova Scotia having closed parks and beaches to the public under its emergency measures act.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6748452/halifax-police-issue-ticket-covid-19-emergency-order/|title=Halifax police seize vehicle, issue ticket to woman violating COVID-19 emergency order|publisher=globalnews.ca|date=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 30, the provincial government released a more comprehensive plan for how schools will proceed through the coronavirus pandemic, as well as an online tool for businesses.<ref>{{cite press release|url=https://novascotia.ca/news/release/?id=20200330004 |title=Plan for At-home Student Learning, Online Guidance for Business |publisher=Government of Nova Scotia, Canada |website=Novascotia.ca |date=2020-03-30 |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\nOn March 31, the provincial government announced that a map will be released in the near future online showing where cases are located across the province organized by the four health zones.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Benjamin |first1=Graeme |title=Breakdown of where coronavirus cases are in Nova Scotia coming soon: Strang |url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6755757/20-new-cases-in-nova-scotia/ |website=globalnews.ca |publisher=Global News |date=March 31, 2020|accessdate=April 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn April 1, the province of Nova Scotia renewed the declaration of a state of emergency extending the previous until April 19.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://novascotia.ca/coronavirus/Direction-of-the-Minister-under-a-Declared-State-of-Emergency.pdf|title=Renewal of Provincial State of Emergency by Minister|last=|first=|date=|website=novascotia.ca|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nOn April 6, it was announced that travel was no longer a prerequisite for testing, as community spread had reached levels that anyone could potentially have the virus regardless of travel history.<ref>{{cite press release|url=https://novascotia.ca/news/release/?id=20200406004|title=Measures to Further Help Prevent Spread of COVID-19|publisher=Government of Nova Scotia, Canada|date=2020-04-06|access-date=2020-04-06|url-status=live|website=Novascotia.ca}}</ref>\n\n== Schools and universities ==\n{{Expand section|date=April 2020}}\nIn March, all Nova Scotian universities suspended in-person classes and restricted access to their campuses. Many transitioned to a distance learning model for the remainder of the academic term.<ref>{{Cite news|title=How Nova Scotia universities are dealing with the COVID-19 pandemic|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/in-person-classes-at-dal-king-s-suspended-next-week-1.5497273|last=Patil|first=Anjuli|date=March 13, 2020|access-date=April 3, 2020|url-status=live|work=CBC News}}</ref>\n\n== Economic impact ==\n{{Expand section|date=April 2020}}\nIn February, Nova Scotia's billion dollar lobster industry was negatively impacted by coronavirus, with a large portion of exports previously going to China. Lobster exports became difficult as air cargo carriers began to suspend service. Lobster prices dropped with a glut in the local market due to restricted exports.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Nova Scotia\u2019s lobster industry fears prolonged effects of coronavirus outbreak as exports halted, prices drop|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/article-nova-scotias-lobster-industry-fears-prolonged-effects-of-coronavirus/|last=Mercer|first=Greg|date=February 2, 2020|access-date=April 3, 2020|url-status=live|work=The Globe and Mail}}</ref>\n\nIn March, a number of Nova Scotia distilleries shifted production from alcoholic beverages to alcohol-based hand sanitizers.<ref>{{Cite news|title=These Nova Scotia distilleries are producing hand sanitizer in time of need|url=https://atlantic.ctvnews.ca/these-nova-scotia-distilleries-are-producing-hand-sanitizer-in-time-of-need-1.4858050|last=April|first=Allan|date=March 18, 2020|access-date=April 3, 2020|url-status=live|work=CTV News}}</ref>\n\nAccording to a survey published by Restaurants Canada on April 2, 2020,<ref>{{cite web|first=Marlee |last=Wasser |url=https://www.restaurantscanada.org/industry-news/covid-19-has-cost-the-foodservice-sector-800000-jobs-since-march-1/ |title=COVID-19 has cost the foodservice sector 800,000 jobs since March 1 |website=Restaurants Canada |date=2020-04-02 |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref> approximately 24,500 Nova Scotian restaurant workers have lost their jobs. Staff have been laid off at about four out of five Nova Scotia restaurants since the beginning of March, around one tenth of restaurants have permanently closed, and a further 18 percent expect to close within a month if nothing changes. Some restaurants have been able to pivot to a take-out or delivery only business model in order to maintain cash flow amid mandatory closures of dining areas.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Coronavirus: Amid record job losses, Nova Scotia restaurant owners innovate|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6767133/record-job-losses-ns-restaurants-innovate/|last=McSheffrey|first=Elizabeth|date=April 2, 2020|access-date=April 3, 2020|url-status=live|work=Global News}}</ref>\n\n== Data ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+COVID-19 cases in Nova Scotia\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Date\n! colspan=\"3\" |Presumptive\n! colspan=\"2\" |Confirmed\n! colspan=\"2\" |Deaths\n! colspan=\"2\" |Recoveries\n! rowspan=\"2\" |{{abbr|HC|Hospitalized cases}}\n! rowspan=\"2\" |{{abbr|NT|Negative tests}}\n! rowspan=\"2\" |{{abbr|TT|Total tests}}\n! rowspan=\"2\" |{